[Guest]: Hi, Amit.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:40.720
[Amit Varma]: It's great to be here.

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:44.560
[Amit Varma]: So you know, when I read your wonderful piece in The Wire, the first thing that struck me

00:02:44.560 --> 00:02:46.080
[Amit Varma]: was how angry you were.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.440
[Amit Varma]: You described it as the death of justice in India.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:52.360
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit more about the case.

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:58.560
[Guest]: So there were a few things going on in this particular case that really distressed me.

00:02:58.560 --> 00:03:04.480
[Guest]: So as we all know, there was a sexual harassment complaint by one of the staff members of the

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:10.080
[Guest]: Supreme Court of India who worked for the current Chief Justice, Justice Ranjan Gogoi.

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:15.520
[Guest]: And she sent an affidavit to the other 22 justices of the Supreme Court and requested

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:21.640
[Guest]: an inquiry into her complaint that she had been subject to sexual harassment and abuse.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:26.560
[Guest]: Now it just so happens that the Supreme Court of India was the front runner when it came

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:28.480
[Guest]: to sexual harassment.

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:33.680
[Guest]: This is in a judgment called Vishakha v. State of Rajasthan, which was far back, like in

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:42.020
[Guest]: 1997 and well before there was any MeToo movement or even any serious recognition of the problem

00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:46.280
[Guest]: of sexual harassment at the workplace by any other institution in the country, the Supreme

00:03:46.280 --> 00:03:49.000
[Guest]: Court said, we need to recognize this problem.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:51.780
[Guest]: There is a huge gap in the law.

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:56.480
[Guest]: In a very activist opinion, they actually did what we call now legislating from the

00:03:56.480 --> 00:03:57.480
[Guest]: bench.

00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:00.320
[Guest]: That is in the absence of law, they literally made law.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:06.440
[Guest]: So the Supreme Court provided a series of guidelines on what needs to be done by every

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:11.840
[Guest]: single workplace in India to prevent sexual harassment and how to deal with the complaints.

00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:15.680
[Guest]: And these guidelines were things like, there needs to be a committee, the committee should

00:04:15.680 --> 00:04:21.720
[Guest]: have at least 50% women, it needs to meet certain criteria, there must be an external

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:24.360
[Guest]: member to the committee and so on and so forth.

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:28.800
[Guest]: And it is this internal committee where any sexual harassment complaint would be reported

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:31.720
[Guest]: and they would deal with it swiftly.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:36.680
[Guest]: And they said that in the absence of any legislation, these guidelines would be law.

00:04:36.680 --> 00:04:42.080
[Guest]: And then eventually, many years later, the parliament did pass legislation on sexual

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:43.480
[Guest]: harassment.

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:48.480
[Guest]: So one would think that given that the Supreme Court was the front runner on this, and they

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:52.200
[Guest]: are the ones who had actually come up with the guidelines.

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:57.640
[Guest]: And given the fact that these are all members trained in law, they serve in the highest

00:04:57.640 --> 00:05:04.560
[Guest]: court of the country, that they would know what to do swiftly and justly.

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:10.520
[Guest]: And what happened immediately after was a series of horrific events.

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:15.200
[Guest]: So the first thing that happened was that the Secretary General of the Supreme Court,

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:21.600
[Guest]: before anything, like overnight, before any committee had been formed or anything else,

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:26.520
[Guest]: just said that these are mischievous and false accusations.

00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:28.520
[Guest]: They're trying to malign the institution.

00:05:28.520 --> 00:05:34.540
[Guest]: And it's like the opposition and other interfering forces are trying to reduce the stature of

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:36.120
[Guest]: the judiciary.

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:41.160
[Guest]: So first of all, it seems like there are other members of the staff who had already come

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:46.360
[Guest]: out in judgment immediately after the affidavit and the complaint had been sent, even before

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:48.480
[Guest]: anything else had been done.

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:53.280
[Guest]: And this is obviously extremely inappropriate for any institution, but for the Supreme Court,

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:55.720
[Guest]: it's really shocking.

00:05:55.720 --> 00:06:01.920
[Guest]: Immediately after that, what happened is the Chief Justice of India constituted a bench

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:09.080
[Guest]: and in this particular bench to hear this matter, he sat on the bench himself along

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:14.520
[Guest]: with two other justices, Justice Khanna and Justice Arun Mishra, not Deepak Mishra.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:20.440
[Guest]: So you can imagine that the most fundamental principle of natural justice, which is that

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:27.600
[Guest]: one shall not sit in judgment of one's own cause was completely violated and by the highest

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:30.120
[Guest]: judicial officer of the country.

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:35.440
[Guest]: And in this particular bench, what they were determining was, it was in reference and they

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:41.320
[Guest]: said they called it a matter of the highest public interest or public concern.

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:47.160
[Guest]: And they basically sat in judgment on whether the complaint is valid or not, right?

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:52.440
[Guest]: And you can imagine that the person heading the bench is the person against whom the complaint

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:53.560
[Guest]: is made.

00:06:53.560 --> 00:06:58.520
[Guest]: So even someone completely untrained in law, a two year old would understand that this

00:06:58.520 --> 00:07:02.080
[Guest]: is not fair or just.

00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:08.120
[Guest]: Now when it was pointed out that this is a problem, by they I mean the Supreme Court

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:15.580
[Guest]: decided to have an internal committee or an ICC as they call it in the Sexual Harassment

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:17.440
[Guest]: at the Workplace Act.

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:25.360
[Guest]: So the ICC had three justices, Justice Ramana, Justice Indira Banerjee and Justice Bhopte.

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:32.240
[Guest]: Now the problem was Justice Ramana before he sat on this particular internal committee

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:38.000
[Guest]: had already revealed to the press that he thought this was a false complaint.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
[Guest]: So once again, someone who had already sat in judgment of the matter and really didn't

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.240
[Guest]: have an open mind was placed on this committee.

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:50.080
[Guest]: So when the complainant brought this to his attention, he had to recuse himself.

00:07:50.080 --> 00:07:53.700
[Guest]: The complainant also brought another fact to their attention saying that it had only

00:07:53.700 --> 00:08:00.240
[Guest]: one woman on the panel, whereas the POSH guidelines require that there should be at least 50%

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:02.760
[Guest]: of the committee has to be women.

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:08.760
[Guest]: So then they replaced Justice Ramana with Justice Indu Malhotra.

00:08:08.760 --> 00:08:15.080
[Guest]: And this particular panel sat and met, there were other violations of their own POSH guidelines,

00:08:15.080 --> 00:08:17.320
[Guest]: which is that there was no external member.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:19.840
[Guest]: She was not allowed to bring a lawyer to the proceedings.

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:22.040
[Guest]: The proceedings weren't recorded.

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:25.880
[Guest]: No external member was allowed to participate in it.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:33.520
[Guest]: And all this was basically some kind of like an internal mechanism to deal with a problem

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:35.740
[Guest]: against their own superior.

00:08:35.740 --> 00:08:40.440
[Guest]: So it was very clear that the other justices were also floundering because basically they're

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:43.200
[Guest]: hearing something against their boss.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:47.160
[Guest]: So in this kind of a panel, it's even more important that an external member be present

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:52.640
[Guest]: and that external member be someone of a very, very high stature, which is quite easy for

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:53.640
[Guest]: the Supreme Court.

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:59.440
[Guest]: You know, they can bring in a retired justice, they can bring in a retired female justice,

00:08:59.440 --> 00:09:04.180
[Guest]: you know, like Justice Rumapal or someone else who has such a stellar reputation.

00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:08.840
[Guest]: So this could have very easily been avoided, but clearly they didn't want to avoid it.

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:15.160
[Guest]: And finally, what happened is the complainant withdrew her complaint, not because she admitted

00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:17.560
[Guest]: that, you know, this was not a genuine complaint.

00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:24.480
[Guest]: She said she has absolutely no hope of getting a fair hearing or justice with this panel

00:09:24.480 --> 00:09:27.000
[Guest]: at this institution.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.760
[Guest]: And she is unfortunately right.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:34.920
[Guest]: And it just really distressed me like this entire series of events.

00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:39.020
[Guest]: It felt like the Supreme Court was doubling down on each mistake one after the other.

00:09:39.020 --> 00:09:41.120
[Amit Varma]: And it just really distressed me.

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:45.640
[Amit Varma]: And isn't it the case that all of these guidelines, which this so-called posh committee did not

00:09:45.640 --> 00:09:50.080
[Amit Varma]: follow were guidelines originally set by the Supreme Court itself, right?

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:51.080
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:57.180
[Guest]: So they seem to behave in a fashion that the rules they make must apply to everyone else

00:09:57.180 --> 00:09:59.280
[Guest]: and they must not apply to themselves.

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:03.320
[Amit Varma]: So wouldn't you say that in a sense that the court could itself be set to be in contempt

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:04.320
[Amit Varma]: of court?

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:14.320
[Guest]: Yes and no, because the contempt laws are not following a very specific judgment, right?

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:18.600
[Guest]: But the court also has the ability to interpret rules in its own way.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:22.360
[Guest]: So this is a play of words and you could go either way with this.

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:27.040
[Guest]: But yes, if you strictly think of it as the same rules that apply to everyone else must

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:33.100
[Guest]: also apply to the members of the judiciary, then they are really violating all of those

00:10:33.100 --> 00:10:34.100
[Guest]: principles.

00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:37.800
[Guest]: In a very brazen way, like all this is not hidden.

00:10:37.800 --> 00:10:44.040
[Guest]: This is all happening in, it's playing out in the media, only partially playing out in

00:10:44.040 --> 00:10:45.040
[Guest]: the media.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:47.280
[Guest]: Frankly, the media was muzzled quite a bit.

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:52.000
[Guest]: A lot of newspapers are scared to run stories about the Supreme Court because they're worried

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:53.600
[Guest]: they'll be held in contempt.

00:10:53.600 --> 00:10:55.800
[Guest]: A lot of people are scared to speak up.

00:10:55.800 --> 00:10:59.600
[Guest]: The people most qualified to speak up are from the legal community who unfortunately

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:02.660
[Guest]: have a lot of cases pending before the judiciary.

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:06.960
[Guest]: So even though the Bar Council and the Supreme Court advocates on record and all these people

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:15.500
[Guest]: came forward and they issued statements condemning the procedural mess, it's very difficult for

00:11:15.500 --> 00:11:21.080
[Guest]: scrutiny to come from people who really depend on the Chief Justice of India to get the matters

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:22.080
[Guest]: through.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:26.800
[Guest]: So there's a really big problem, you know, systemic problem that is taking place.

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:31.220
[Amit Varma]: And what's also kind of bizarre is, as you wrote in your piece, is that the case became

00:11:31.220 --> 00:11:36.960
[Amit Varma]: politicized very fast with cabinet ministers jumping in to defend the Chief Justice where

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:38.400
[Amit Varma]: it had really nothing to do with them.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:42.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, why should they get involved?

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:45.480
[Guest]: So this is the thing that is very worrying, right?

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:53.360
[Guest]: So it seems like any time, so, okay, to me in a civilized society, no one should know

00:11:53.360 --> 00:12:00.400
[Guest]: names of specific justices, you know, to me, that would be the most civilized society of

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:01.400
[Guest]: all.

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:04.920
[Guest]: You know, maybe, you know, if there was a new Chief Justice sworn in or something, you

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:11.120
[Guest]: know his name, but justice should be based on principles so much so that it doesn't have

00:12:11.120 --> 00:12:13.520
[Guest]: any individuals deep imprint on it.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:17.920
[Guest]: And we don't think of individuals as partisan and taking sides.

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:22.640
[Guest]: When the government and cabinet ministers, the Attorney General, the Solicitor General,

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:28.060
[Guest]: they all came out of the woodwork within hours, they completely rubbish the complaint and

00:12:28.060 --> 00:12:33.800
[Guest]: malign the reputation of the complainant without knowing all the facts because the complaint

00:12:33.800 --> 00:12:37.920
[Guest]: had been made like 48 hours before all this happened.

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:42.240
[Guest]: And they immediately took the side of the Chief Justice, which shows that something

00:12:42.240 --> 00:12:43.440
[Guest]: is going on, right?

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:47.960
[Guest]: They want, they think he's their guy or they want him to be at the helm and they don't

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:51.520
[Guest]: want him to resign or be impeached and so on.

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:56.460
[Guest]: So that makes one extremely suspicious of what is going on.

00:12:56.460 --> 00:13:04.360
[Guest]: And if you remember Chief Justice Gogoi, who was just a, you know, a senior justice prior

00:13:04.360 --> 00:13:09.320
[Guest]: to this, when Deepak Mishra was the Chief Justice, there was a press conference that

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:12.020
[Guest]: before senior most judges held.

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:18.680
[Guest]: And the only person who flipped his stance later was Justice Gogoi.

00:13:18.680 --> 00:13:22.840
[Guest]: And he was the next in line to be appointed Chief Justice of India.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:29.680
[Guest]: And it all seems very messy and complicated in terms of it's very opaque on how justices

00:13:29.680 --> 00:13:33.720
[Guest]: and Chief Justices are appointed and promoted.

00:13:33.720 --> 00:13:42.560
[Guest]: So it's very unclear where the alliances lie, and precisely why the current government and

00:13:42.560 --> 00:13:46.680
[Guest]: the current executive want to support this particular Chief Justice.

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:53.280
[Amit Varma]: Right, so let's step back for a moment and, you know, take a much broader view of what

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:57.400
[Amit Varma]: our justice system is like, what is the role the Supreme Court plays in it?

00:13:57.400 --> 00:13:58.680
[Amit Varma]: What are its duties?

00:13:58.680 --> 00:14:00.280
[Amit Varma]: What is it supposed to do?

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:05.240
[Amit Varma]: So now, you know, we can get a clearer sense of what is going wrong specifically now.

00:14:05.240 --> 00:14:10.740
[Amit Varma]: So take me back in time, like, you know, our modern justice system as it is now really

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:13.240
[Amit Varma]: came about in 1950, right?

00:14:13.240 --> 00:14:14.240
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:19.560
[Guest]: So a little bit before that, in the sense that we had a functioning set of high courts,

00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:22.920
[Guest]: and a federal court, which was called the British Federal Court, which eventually became

00:14:22.920 --> 00:14:23.920
[Guest]: the Supreme Court.

00:14:23.920 --> 00:14:27.520
[Guest]: Of course, at the time, the British Federal Court was not the highest court of appeal,

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:31.640
[Guest]: the Privy Council in London was the highest court of appeal.

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:37.400
[Guest]: So in that sense, you know, sort of the infrastructure we inherited from colonial times, but the

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:46.160
[Guest]: constitution making process from 1946 to 1950, one of the big differences, so as you know,

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:52.360
[Guest]: India inherited or at least pretty much exactly adopted the existing parliamentary system,

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:53.360
[Guest]: right?

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:57.760
[Guest]: So whatever was the British Westminster system was continued in India, and, you know, very

00:14:57.760 --> 00:14:59.720
[Guest]: few tweaks were made to it.

00:14:59.720 --> 00:15:05.280
[Guest]: But there was one major difference from the colonial government, which is England does

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:10.320
[Guest]: not, or at least at that time, did not have independent judicial review.

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:14.800
[Guest]: That is an American inheritance for us, right?

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:20.040
[Guest]: What we mean by independent judicial review is that the judiciary will provide a check

00:15:20.040 --> 00:15:26.160
[Guest]: and a balance, both to the executive and to the legislature.

00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:32.440
[Guest]: So if the executive makes any kinds of actions, which are unconstitutional, the institution

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:38.320
[Guest]: that will adjudicate whether or not it is unconstitutional, and then nullify that particular

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:40.600
[Guest]: order is the judiciary.

00:15:40.600 --> 00:15:45.920
[Guest]: This comes from an old court case called Marbury versus Madison in America.

00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:49.840
[Guest]: That was the sort of the starting point of independent judicial review.

00:15:49.840 --> 00:15:54.320
[Guest]: Now in that particular case, it also applied to the legislature, right?

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:57.960
[Guest]: Now this was not true of England.

00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:03.480
[Guest]: The parliament could only, was sovereign in England, sovereign in the sense, you know,

00:16:03.480 --> 00:16:09.440
[Guest]: in terms of checks and balances, and the courts could only review executive action, but they

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:13.720
[Guest]: could not review legislative action, right?

00:16:13.720 --> 00:16:18.960
[Guest]: So this is one major difference between what was going on in England in 1950 and what was

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:21.360
[Guest]: happening in India in 1950.

00:16:21.360 --> 00:16:27.240
[Guest]: And Ambedkar, who of course studied at Columbia and a whole host of other legal minds in India

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:32.000
[Guest]: who were very inspired by the American system, thought that it is crucial to have independent

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:37.680
[Guest]: judicial review in a constitutional setup that guarantees fundamental rights.

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:43.400
[Guest]: So you need to have writ jurisdiction, which means there are a host of writs that individuals

00:16:43.400 --> 00:16:48.560
[Guest]: have where they can petition the court and say, my rights have been violated, and you

00:16:48.560 --> 00:16:54.520
[Guest]: need to look into this matter and therefore either approve or nullify the executive action

00:16:54.520 --> 00:17:00.400
[Guest]: or the particular, you know, bill or act, which has violated my rights.

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:07.480
[Guest]: Now, incidentally, the court took to this immediately and very quickly, like all the

00:17:07.480 --> 00:17:13.120
[Guest]: justices who were justices at the time of the birth of the republic, they were very

00:17:13.120 --> 00:17:17.480
[Guest]: well versed with what independent judicial review means, even though they hadn't come

00:17:17.480 --> 00:17:19.040
[Guest]: from that system.

00:17:19.040 --> 00:17:23.800
[Guest]: So they knew how to interpret the law, they knew how to think about these principles,

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:29.680
[Guest]: and they knew that for the constitution to have any real value, you need to be able to

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:37.640
[Guest]: very clearly define when legislation and when executive action violates the constitution.

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:40.440
[Guest]: And that's really where independent judicial review comes in from.

00:17:40.440 --> 00:17:45.400
[Guest]: Now, why is it important that this kind of judicial review is independent?

00:17:45.400 --> 00:17:52.440
[Guest]: It is so that the judiciary is not subject to the arbitrary actions of the executive

00:17:52.440 --> 00:17:56.040
[Guest]: for the legislature, right, that it has its own place.

00:17:56.040 --> 00:18:00.640
[Guest]: And one of the ways to make the judiciary independent is that its appointment procedure

00:18:00.640 --> 00:18:02.940
[Guest]: is independent, right?

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:07.000
[Guest]: So that is really where this kind of system comes from.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:13.000
[Guest]: Ambedkar was a very big advocate to push through this kind of independent judicial review.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:19.080
[Guest]: And he felt that the judiciary must be both independent of the executive, but it also

00:18:19.080 --> 00:18:21.000
[Guest]: needs to be competent.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.720
[Guest]: So how do you balance these two things, right?

00:18:23.720 --> 00:18:30.240
[Guest]: Now, the executive represents the people of India after being elected through the legislature.

00:18:30.240 --> 00:18:34.740
[Guest]: They are the people who really govern, so they are the ones in charge of the appointments.

00:18:34.740 --> 00:18:40.200
[Guest]: But how do we make sure that the people making appointments are also removed from the people

00:18:40.200 --> 00:18:41.920
[Guest]: whom they appoint?

00:18:41.920 --> 00:18:46.520
[Guest]: So there are a whole host of procedures to make sure that the judiciary is independent.

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:51.680
[Guest]: One of these is that no high court or Supreme Court judge can be removed except for an impeachment

00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:53.960
[Guest]: proceeding, right?

00:18:53.960 --> 00:19:00.080
[Guest]: So judicial officers at the highest courts can only be impeached, they can't just be,

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:02.040
[Guest]: you know, dismissed.

00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:06.640
[Guest]: And they have a term which ends when they reach the age of 62 in the case of the high

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:09.140
[Guest]: courts and 65 in the case of the Supreme Court.

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:14.560
[Guest]: So they only retire based on their date of birth, right, they can't be manipulated and

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:18.840
[Guest]: forced to retire early or pushed or get an extension or retire later.

00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:21.480
[Guest]: So there were a bunch of safeguards like this.

00:19:21.480 --> 00:19:28.960
[Guest]: And the most important part of this procedure was Article 124 for the Supreme Court appointments

00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:36.040
[Guest]: and Article 217 for the high court appointments, which basically said that the president shall

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:37.040
[Guest]: make the appointment.

00:19:37.040 --> 00:19:43.560
[Guest]: And when we say the president, we really mean the cabinet, and he shall do so in consultation

00:19:43.560 --> 00:19:47.400
[Guest]: with the Chief Justice of India, right?

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:53.560
[Guest]: And now, for the last 70 plus years, there is a huge question over what is the meaning

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:56.880
[Guest]: of the word consultation, right?

00:19:56.880 --> 00:20:00.440
[Guest]: In case of a disagreement, whose voice prevails?

00:20:00.440 --> 00:20:04.360
[Guest]: You know, does the Chief Justice's view become binding?

00:20:04.360 --> 00:20:07.080
[Guest]: Does the cabinet's view become binding?

00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:11.920
[Guest]: And exactly how do you deal with this problem, right, when there is a disagreement?

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:17.480
[Guest]: So that has been sort of the centerpiece of independence of judiciary in India for the

00:20:17.480 --> 00:20:19.300
[Guest]: last 70 years.

00:20:19.300 --> 00:20:24.240
[Amit Varma]: So let me try to kind of recap that and tell me if I understood it correctly.

00:20:24.240 --> 00:20:31.760
[Amit Varma]: Basically, it wasn't always the case that the judiciary is independent of both the executive

00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:33.320
[Amit Varma]: and the legislature.

00:20:33.320 --> 00:20:38.700
[Amit Varma]: And what Ambedkar did was he followed the American precedent of making it independent

00:20:38.700 --> 00:20:42.280
[Amit Varma]: of both the executive and the legislature and the purpose of the judiciary therefore

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:47.680
[Amit Varma]: became to ensure that the rules that were set in the Constitution and our laws applied

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:53.360
[Amit Varma]: to everybody equally, including the executive and the legislature, which brings about the

00:20:53.360 --> 00:21:00.840
[Amit Varma]: dilemma of how do you do this, if the judiciary itself is going to be appointed by the people

00:21:00.840 --> 00:21:02.440
[Amit Varma]: who it's supposed to control?

00:21:02.440 --> 00:21:06.160
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, you and I have discussed and this was again a question I had for a

00:21:06.160 --> 00:21:10.840
[Amit Varma]: later part, but might as well bring it up now is that, you know, the same way that we

00:21:10.840 --> 00:21:15.680
[Amit Varma]: apply public choice theory to governments where we talk about, you know, the incentives

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:21.360
[Amit Varma]: in play, a, I guess the same principles would apply to the judiciary and B, in this case,

00:21:21.360 --> 00:21:28.840
[Amit Varma]: it would seem to me that the incentives for those in government would always be to select

00:21:28.840 --> 00:21:35.120
[Amit Varma]: pliant judges, and then keep seeding the Supreme Courts and the high courts with pliant judges

00:21:35.120 --> 00:21:38.000
[Amit Varma]: and manipulate the system in that way.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:43.160
[Amit Varma]: So what is sort of a history of those kinds of tensions playing out?

00:21:43.160 --> 00:21:47.560
[Amit Varma]: And how has the judiciary stayed independent to begin with, for whatever time it did stay

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:48.560
[Guest]: independent?

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:52.560
[Guest]: So you have really hit the pulse of the matter.

00:21:52.560 --> 00:21:56.600
[Guest]: So you and I have talked a lot about, you know, what are the kind of rules in place

00:21:56.600 --> 00:21:59.560
[Guest]: and what are the incentives based on the rules.

00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:06.960
[Guest]: But I want to also state the importance of convention and of statesman like leaders here

00:22:06.960 --> 00:22:08.120
[Guest]: a little bit.

00:22:08.120 --> 00:22:13.840
[Guest]: So in the 1950s, you know, when, so what happened was that the Chief Justice of the British

00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:18.340
[Guest]: Federal Court was Chief Justice Kanya, when we adopted the constitution.

00:22:18.340 --> 00:22:22.560
[Guest]: So the day we adopted the constitution, the British Federal Court became the Supreme Court

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:27.040
[Guest]: of India, and Chief Justice Kanya became the Chief Justice of India.

00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:34.840
[Guest]: Okay, when Chief Justice Kanya died in office soon after, the next most senior justice was

00:22:34.840 --> 00:22:37.240
[Guest]: Justice Patanjali Shastri.

00:22:37.240 --> 00:22:42.120
[Guest]: Now it is believed that Nehru, who was at the time the Prime Minister and therefore

00:22:42.120 --> 00:22:48.140
[Guest]: representing the cabinet, he preferred Justice MC Mahajan, who was at the Bombay High Court

00:22:48.140 --> 00:22:49.860
[Guest]: at the time.

00:22:49.860 --> 00:22:53.640
[Guest]: And it was quite clear that that was his preference.

00:22:53.640 --> 00:22:59.460
[Guest]: But all the Supreme Court justices threatened to resign if the next most senior justice

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:02.560
[Guest]: did not automatically become the Chief Justice.

00:23:02.560 --> 00:23:08.000
[Guest]: And that is really the beginning of the convention that the next senior most justice will become

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:13.960
[Guest]: the Chief Justice and serve whether that term is for two days or for 10 years.

00:23:13.960 --> 00:23:18.100
[Guest]: You know, this is not written anywhere in the constitution, like there's no text that

00:23:18.100 --> 00:23:20.680
[Guest]: supports this, but it is convention.

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:26.640
[Guest]: And it is also like we must applaud Nehru that when he felt that there was pushback

00:23:26.640 --> 00:23:28.720
[Guest]: from the judiciary on one of his decisions.

00:23:28.720 --> 00:23:34.680
[Guest]: And by the way, Justice MC Mahajan was a legendary judge, right?

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:38.680
[Guest]: This is a time actually when the Supreme Court of India, which used to be the British Federal

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:41.320
[Guest]: Court, was really not that important.

00:23:41.320 --> 00:23:43.760
[Guest]: You know, they were the highest court of appeal.

00:23:43.760 --> 00:23:48.360
[Guest]: They got very few cases, usually on like very boring matters of law.

00:23:48.360 --> 00:23:53.320
[Guest]: The busy and important courts for the high courts, they did the bulk of the work.

00:23:53.320 --> 00:23:57.720
[Guest]: So it was really your high court judges who were sort of superstars.

00:23:57.720 --> 00:24:04.280
[Guest]: And it seems like Nehru picked one such superstar, you know, who had, I mean, it's not like he

00:24:04.280 --> 00:24:09.640
[Guest]: just picked some random client guy, like he was really, by any standards, an excellent

00:24:09.640 --> 00:24:10.640
[Guest]: judge.

00:24:10.640 --> 00:24:15.840
[Guest]: But Nehru knew when to step back and respect the authority of institutions.

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:21.160
[Guest]: And Nehru was so popular, frankly, he had said, yeah, go ahead and resign.

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:23.560
[Guest]: You know, this is a country full of British trained lawyers.

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:25.520
[Guest]: I can replace you guys tomorrow.

00:24:25.520 --> 00:24:27.200
[Guest]: He could have easily done that.

00:24:27.200 --> 00:24:34.240
[Guest]: But Nehru knew that there will never be respect for the Supreme Court if it wasn't viewed

00:24:34.240 --> 00:24:37.920
[Guest]: as independent by all the stakeholders in society.

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:39.840
[Guest]: So he knew when to step back.

00:24:39.840 --> 00:24:45.200
[Guest]: So I want to, you know, sort of emphasize the importance of convention here.

00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:50.560
[Guest]: It is very difficult to put down every rule in writing and then interpret every rule,

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:55.840
[Guest]: especially by the same court that, you know, needs to interpret the rule in its own matter.

00:24:55.840 --> 00:24:59.600
[Guest]: So in these kinds of situations, the convention really kicks in.

00:24:59.600 --> 00:25:09.440
[Guest]: And from 1951 to 1973, we had a very clear procedure of appointment.

00:25:09.440 --> 00:25:14.160
[Guest]: It was, of course, I mean, even in those years, there are some examples where it seems like

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:16.320
[Guest]: there's some executive influence.

00:25:16.320 --> 00:25:22.760
[Guest]: But it largely seems like very good, qualified people were appointed, that the Chief Justice

00:25:22.760 --> 00:25:28.200
[Guest]: of India's opinion always had very, very high consideration or regard.

00:25:28.200 --> 00:25:33.880
[Guest]: And if there were politically motivated appointments or transfers, it wasn't a rampant thing.

00:25:33.880 --> 00:25:36.680
[Guest]: It might have been a one-off thing, right?

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:39.600
[Guest]: So that's the situation until 1973.

00:25:39.600 --> 00:25:45.720
[Guest]: Now, you and I have talked about, in an episode, we've talked about property rights for over

00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:47.200
[Guest]: an hour.

00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:50.960
[Guest]: And if we just reference back to that episode, we talked about how the constitution kept

00:25:50.960 --> 00:25:56.520
[Guest]: getting amended by the parliament, especially by the Indira Gandhi government, because the

00:25:56.520 --> 00:26:01.720
[Guest]: judiciary kept interpreting the constitution as it is written, right?

00:26:01.720 --> 00:26:06.960
[Guest]: So one of the consequences of that was that if you keep amending the constitution, the

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:09.320
[Guest]: courts are going to say, hey, this is very problematic.

00:26:09.320 --> 00:26:14.440
[Guest]: You can't just amend the constitution anytime we enforce the constitution.

00:26:14.440 --> 00:26:22.680
[Guest]: So in 1967, there's a case called Golaknath, where the Supreme Court in 11 judge bench

00:26:22.680 --> 00:26:27.920
[Guest]: held that the constitution is unamendable by the parliament, that fundamental rights

00:26:27.920 --> 00:26:29.160
[Guest]: cannot be amended.

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:31.400
[Guest]: This was in 1967.

00:26:31.400 --> 00:26:37.520
[Guest]: Now the matter got appealed and in a case called Kesavanandarthi versus State of Kerala.

00:26:37.520 --> 00:26:39.360
[Guest]: And this was a 13 judge bench.

00:26:39.360 --> 00:26:44.720
[Guest]: Again, the question was, does the parliament have the authority to amend the constitution?

00:26:44.720 --> 00:26:50.360
[Guest]: And this is the case where the basic structure doctrine was created and the court basically

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:54.880
[Guest]: said that the parliament has the authority to amend the constitution, but this is not

00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:56.280
[Guest]: an unlimited authority.

00:26:56.280 --> 00:27:01.240
[Guest]: There is a core to the constitution that is inviolable and unamendable.

00:27:01.240 --> 00:27:03.280
[Guest]: We call that the basic structure.

00:27:03.280 --> 00:27:08.040
[Guest]: Basically it is things like federalism, democracy, secularism, independent judiciary, and so

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:09.040
[Guest]: on.

00:27:09.040 --> 00:27:13.920
[Guest]: And if the parliament amends any of these parts, we can strike down that constitutional

00:27:13.920 --> 00:27:14.920
[Guest]: amendment.

00:27:14.920 --> 00:27:19.760
[Guest]: Now, the interesting thing is in this particular case, the court didn't say exactly what the

00:27:19.760 --> 00:27:21.400
[Guest]: basic structure of the constitution is.

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:23.960
[Guest]: They didn't give us a list, right?

00:27:23.960 --> 00:27:28.680
[Guest]: They said, we will know when we see it, we'll decide on a case by case basis.

00:27:28.680 --> 00:27:34.560
[Guest]: There's a lot of politics and it's a fascinating story how this case came about, but the decision

00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:41.640
[Guest]: was given on April 24, 1973, which was also the last date of the term of Chief Justice

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:43.160
[Guest]: Sikri.

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:49.080
[Guest]: So Chief Justice Sikri knew that this is going to create a huge fallout.

00:27:49.080 --> 00:27:55.160
[Guest]: And as soon as it is announced, they wrote their separate opinions.

00:27:55.160 --> 00:28:01.160
[Guest]: Chief H.R. Khanna was one of the instrumental people in coming up with the basic structure

00:28:01.160 --> 00:28:02.960
[Guest]: of the constitution.

00:28:02.960 --> 00:28:05.960
[Guest]: And it was a seven, six judgment.

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:10.000
[Guest]: And there were like lots of dissenting opinions, really convoluted, it runs into thousands

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:11.000
[Guest]: of pages.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:16.760
[Guest]: And one of the justices who wholeheartedly was on the side of the government was Justice

00:28:16.760 --> 00:28:19.360
[Guest]: A.N. Ray.

00:28:19.360 --> 00:28:24.640
[Guest]: So when Chief Justice Sikri retired, there were three justices, right?

00:28:24.640 --> 00:28:29.320
[Guest]: Justice Shellach, Justice Grover, Justice Hegde, who were next in line.

00:28:29.320 --> 00:28:32.120
[Guest]: And then there was Justice A.N. Ray.

00:28:32.120 --> 00:28:38.560
[Guest]: Now Indira Gandhi, knowing that these justices had sided against the government in this particular

00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:43.440
[Guest]: opinion, violated what is the fundamental principle of independent judiciary, which

00:28:43.440 --> 00:28:48.360
[Guest]: is that justices must not be rewarded or penalized for their judicial opinions.

00:28:48.360 --> 00:28:54.640
[Guest]: So the day after Sikri retires, instead of appointing the next in line, she supersedes

00:28:54.640 --> 00:29:01.680
[Guest]: three senior judges and then appoints Justice A.N. Ray as the Chief Justice of India.

00:29:01.680 --> 00:29:06.720
[Guest]: And this is the first time anything like this had happened in India.

00:29:06.720 --> 00:29:08.900
[Guest]: It was like a complete shock.

00:29:08.900 --> 00:29:12.360
[Guest]: Of course, this is the time of like great statesman.

00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:18.440
[Guest]: And within a day, justices Shellach, Grover, Hegde, all of them resigned from the bench,

00:29:18.440 --> 00:29:19.440
[Guest]: right?

00:29:19.440 --> 00:29:21.720
[Guest]: So in a sense, Indira Gandhi got exactly what she wanted.

00:29:21.720 --> 00:29:26.180
[Guest]: She superseded three justices who were against her, which created three vacancies.

00:29:26.180 --> 00:29:31.200
[Guest]: And now she had A.N. Ray, who was known as her man, though it's not clear if there was

00:29:31.200 --> 00:29:36.880
[Guest]: any specific reward and punishment system between A.N. Ray and the government.

00:29:36.880 --> 00:29:42.560
[Guest]: And she was hoping that A.N. Ray will reconstitute a bench within a month or so and re-look at

00:29:42.560 --> 00:29:43.560
[Guest]: Keshavanand Bharti.

00:29:43.560 --> 00:29:45.600
[Guest]: Now, thankfully, that didn't happen.

00:29:45.600 --> 00:29:47.560
[Guest]: And that's a whole other story.

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:53.720
[Guest]: But this is the first instance of this kind of seniority being violated.

00:29:53.720 --> 00:29:59.500
[Guest]: Indira Gandhi also started or at least pushed forth the trend of transferring justices when

00:29:59.500 --> 00:30:04.040
[Guest]: they gave opinions against the government, right?

00:30:04.040 --> 00:30:09.960
[Guest]: This is most evident in cases like ADM, Shivkanth Shukla.

00:30:09.960 --> 00:30:16.340
[Guest]: This is the habeas corpus case at the peak of the emergency, right?

00:30:16.340 --> 00:30:21.760
[Guest]: And Justice Rangarajan, who was then the high court judge, who gave the judgment, was immediately

00:30:21.760 --> 00:30:29.120
[Guest]: transferred to Guwahati High Court, which is kind of a penalty posting, as they say,

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:30.120
[Guest]: right?

00:30:30.120 --> 00:30:34.600
[Guest]: There are some big high courts from where you typically get moved up, and that's what

00:30:34.600 --> 00:30:37.080
[Guest]: happened to Justice Rangarajan.

00:30:37.080 --> 00:30:41.320
[Guest]: Justice HR Khanna, who when, you know, ADM Shivkanth Shukla was appealed to the Supreme

00:30:41.320 --> 00:30:47.360
[Guest]: Court, he gave his opinion against the government and against the government actions and held

00:30:47.360 --> 00:30:50.400
[Guest]: up the fundamental rights of individuals.

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:57.080
[Guest]: And when he was the next senior most justice, he was superseded, right?

00:30:57.080 --> 00:31:03.160
[Guest]: So once again, Justice Baig, who was junior to Justice HR Khanna, was made chief justice

00:31:03.160 --> 00:31:07.800
[Guest]: by superseding HR Khanna, immediately the day after HR Khanna resigned, right?

00:31:07.800 --> 00:31:14.400
[Guest]: So there were these two instances where senior Supreme Court judges were superseded, where

00:31:14.400 --> 00:31:19.720
[Guest]: justices at the high court and the Supreme Court were transferred for things that they,

00:31:19.720 --> 00:31:24.440
[Guest]: you know, did in their professional capacity, enforcing independent judicial review, which

00:31:24.440 --> 00:31:26.000
[Guest]: was their job.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:31.560
[Guest]: And this was really a huge attack on the institution of the independence of the judiciary.

00:31:31.560 --> 00:31:37.280
[Guest]: Meanwhile, during the emergency, the Indira Gandhi government also passed the 42nd Amendment,

00:31:37.280 --> 00:31:43.360
[Guest]: which severely restricted independent judicial review, you know, and thankfully the emergency

00:31:43.360 --> 00:31:51.320
[Guest]: ended and Janata government, which came in 77, 78, undid a lot of the 42nd Amendment

00:31:51.320 --> 00:31:56.920
[Guest]: and the 43rd and 44th Amendment, and they restored all the rules of the judiciary back

00:31:56.920 --> 00:32:00.480
[Guest]: to the 1950 set of rules, right?

00:32:00.480 --> 00:32:06.560
[Guest]: So all the mischief was in some sense undone, but the judiciary has never recovered from

00:32:06.560 --> 00:32:13.400
[Guest]: this blow in the sense that there is always a feeling that there is too much executive

00:32:13.400 --> 00:32:20.680
[Guest]: interference and there's always a threat that if any Supreme Court or high court judge gives

00:32:20.680 --> 00:32:24.720
[Guest]: an opinion that is against the government, the government uses all of its influence and

00:32:24.720 --> 00:32:30.640
[Guest]: might to try to undermine the career of that particular judge or to transfer them or to

00:32:30.640 --> 00:32:34.320
[Guest]: make sure that they are never appointed to the Supreme Court if they're a high court

00:32:34.320 --> 00:32:36.060
[Guest]: judge and so on and so forth.

00:32:36.060 --> 00:32:42.280
[Guest]: So this is really the core of the fallout of the actions of Indira Gandhi, right?

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:48.320
[Guest]: So this stuff was brewing a little bit before her also, but before her, we had leaders who

00:32:48.320 --> 00:32:54.480
[Guest]: were statesmen who knew when to stop, you know, the rules were equally unclear all along,

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:58.160
[Guest]: but the statesmen knew when to stop and when not to push.

00:32:58.160 --> 00:33:01.160
[Amit Varma]: So I have kind of three related questions.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:05.400
[Amit Varma]: And what you just said kind of brought me back to the sort of the first of them.

00:33:05.400 --> 00:33:07.360
[Amit Varma]: And I'll ask the first two together.

00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:11.840
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, you and I both agree, and we've often written about how democracies

00:33:11.840 --> 00:33:17.280
[Amit Varma]: and systems of government can't rely on having good people and great leaders at the top.

00:33:17.280 --> 00:33:21.320
[Amit Varma]: Instead, what you need is good rules and good structures.

00:33:21.320 --> 00:33:26.440
[Amit Varma]: So that even if somebody who is a demagogue or a bad person comes to power, they can't

00:33:26.440 --> 00:33:28.040
[Amit Varma]: really do much damage.

00:33:28.040 --> 00:33:31.240
[Amit Varma]: What is important are sort of the rules in place.

00:33:31.240 --> 00:33:36.080
[Amit Varma]: And the first part of this narrative about the independence of the judiciary seems to

00:33:36.080 --> 00:33:42.500
[Amit Varma]: rely on, to begin with, in the first instance, the statesmanship of Nehru in letting that

00:33:42.500 --> 00:33:47.920
[Amit Varma]: convention be established at the senior most judge be made the Chief Justice of India,

00:33:47.920 --> 00:33:52.080
[Amit Varma]: and not insisting on Justice Mahajan getting that post.

00:33:52.080 --> 00:33:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And then that convention continues, because like you said that they were sort of all these

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.040
[Amit Varma]: statesmen who were doing the right thing.

00:33:59.040 --> 00:34:03.160
[Amit Varma]: But then the point is, you can't rely on statesmen doing the right thing for the system to work.

00:34:03.160 --> 00:34:07.320
[Amit Varma]: So my question, therefore, is that, again, like two questions.

00:34:07.320 --> 00:34:13.040
[Amit Varma]: Question number one, what kind of rules should there have been in place that could possibly

00:34:13.040 --> 00:34:18.520
[Amit Varma]: have enforced that kind of independence of the judiciary, number one?

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:25.440
[Amit Varma]: And number two, how does it work in other countries, where also the judiciary is notionally

00:34:25.440 --> 00:34:26.440
[Amit Varma]: independent?

00:34:26.440 --> 00:34:29.360
[Amit Varma]: Like, would the US be an example of another such country?

00:34:29.360 --> 00:34:34.600
[Amit Varma]: And there also the appointment of Supreme Court judges is very politicized, isn't it?

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:36.560
[Guest]: Yeah, so two things.

00:34:36.560 --> 00:34:40.520
[Guest]: So you're absolutely right, you know, you and I, because of our public choice, interest

00:34:40.520 --> 00:34:46.760
[Guest]: and background, we focus on rules and institutions, and we say you can't rely on people.

00:34:46.760 --> 00:34:50.380
[Guest]: Having said that, people do interpret the rules, right?

00:34:50.380 --> 00:34:55.600
[Guest]: So when there are good people, the same set of rules, good or bad, tend to come up with

00:34:55.600 --> 00:34:58.240
[Guest]: slightly better outcomes than when they are bad people.

00:34:58.240 --> 00:35:00.400
[Guest]: But your larger point is absolutely right.

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:04.920
[Guest]: Rules need to be robust to even the worst kind, right?

00:35:04.920 --> 00:35:09.800
[Guest]: My dissertation advisor, Peter Bedke, always used to say, you don't write rules as if Mother

00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:11.720
[Guest]: Teresa is going to enforce them.

00:35:11.720 --> 00:35:14.680
[Guest]: You write rules as if Joseph Stalin is going to enforce them.

00:35:14.680 --> 00:35:16.520
[Amit Varma]: So that still remains true.

00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:20.960
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, what you pointed out earlier, you know, that the controversy over what does

00:35:20.960 --> 00:35:24.480
[Amit Varma]: the word consultation mean and consultation with the CGI.

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:30.320
[Amit Varma]: And I'd imagine that good well framed rules would not leave any ambiguity like that in

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:31.320
[Amit Varma]: the books.

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:32.320
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:35:32.320 --> 00:35:37.960
[Guest]: I mean, this is definitely a flaw in the text of the Constitution.

00:35:37.960 --> 00:35:42.520
[Guest]: I mean, it would be charitable to say that the framers goofed this up, but they really

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:43.680
[Guest]: did mess it up.

00:35:43.680 --> 00:35:48.840
[Guest]: You know, a consultation, deliberation, these are not the kinds of words that you want to

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:51.000
[Guest]: have in a constitutional document.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:56.800
[Guest]: You want to have very, very clear procedures on how people are appointed, right?

00:35:56.800 --> 00:36:05.000
[Guest]: So second, if you do put in the word consultation because you want it to be an amicable decision

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:10.240
[Guest]: as opposed to, you know, pitting one institution against the other, you still need to clarify

00:36:10.240 --> 00:36:14.280
[Guest]: who has supremacy in case of disagreement, right?

00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:22.680
[Guest]: Now in any kind of panel, even judicial benches, we have an odd number of members on the panel.

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:24.400
[Guest]: Now why do we do that?

00:36:24.400 --> 00:36:29.160
[Guest]: Now in an ideal world, we would like opinions to be unanimous or not just have a narrow

00:36:29.160 --> 00:36:34.040
[Guest]: majority, but we still have an odd number because if it's an even number, it could be

00:36:34.040 --> 00:36:37.920
[Guest]: a split and then you don't know where to go from there, right?

00:36:37.920 --> 00:36:44.760
[Guest]: So even our common sense panels and decisions always have odd numbers, right?

00:36:44.760 --> 00:36:48.000
[Guest]: So now odd number panel, those are conventions.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:51.720
[Guest]: Those are not like they are not written in the text of the Constitution, but it's such

00:36:51.720 --> 00:36:54.800
[Guest]: a strong and commonsensical and obvious convention.

00:36:54.800 --> 00:36:58.440
[Guest]: But the reason for the convention is to break deadlock, right?

00:36:58.440 --> 00:37:04.000
[Guest]: So having words like consultation and not having a backup procedure to break deadlock

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:10.400
[Guest]: when the consultative process fails, in my opinion, that is probably the biggest flaw

00:37:10.400 --> 00:37:18.020
[Guest]: in Article 124, Article 217 and Article 222, which is about transfer of judges.

00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:26.800
[Guest]: So one possible defense in the framers is that they were genuinely extraordinary statesmen.

00:37:26.800 --> 00:37:32.320
[Guest]: You know, the people who crafted our constitution, because they were surrounded by other people

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:40.280
[Guest]: like them who were so well-meaning and so well-educated and so public spirited in their

00:37:40.280 --> 00:37:41.280
[Guest]: service.

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:46.880
[Guest]: I think they imagined that is the quality of leaders we will elect and they didn't think

00:37:46.880 --> 00:37:52.640
[Guest]: that there would be a possibility of future elected leaders who would be self-serving

00:37:52.640 --> 00:37:55.760
[Guest]: and violate these documents so badly.

00:37:55.760 --> 00:38:00.640
[Guest]: So that is the most charitable thing I can say in defense of the framers.

00:38:00.640 --> 00:38:04.220
[Guest]: Now coming to your second question, you're absolutely right.

00:38:04.220 --> 00:38:10.000
[Guest]: It is complicated the world over, different countries have different procedures for appointment.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:15.580
[Guest]: In America, the way they have ensured judicial independence is to have a life term appointment

00:38:15.580 --> 00:38:18.320
[Guest]: at the Supreme Court level, right?

00:38:18.320 --> 00:38:20.520
[Guest]: And there are pros and cons of this kind of appointment.

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:27.360
[Guest]: So the pro is once you get on the Supreme Court bench in the US Supreme Court, you serve

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:33.520
[Guest]: until the end of, you know, whenever you choose to step down for medical or health reasons

00:38:33.520 --> 00:38:35.400
[Guest]: or when you die.

00:38:35.400 --> 00:38:38.080
[Guest]: So it's a life appointment, right?

00:38:38.080 --> 00:38:44.480
[Guest]: And that means that justices can serve on the Supreme Court bench for 40 years, 50 years

00:38:44.480 --> 00:38:46.920
[Guest]: if you appoint someone young, right?

00:38:46.920 --> 00:38:47.920
[Guest]: So that's that.

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:56.080
[Guest]: And over 50 years, you are going to give countless decisions every year, but you cannot be penalized

00:38:56.080 --> 00:39:00.920
[Guest]: for any of those decisions, nor can you be rewarded for any of those decisions because

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:03.800
[Guest]: there is no job waiting for you after that.

00:39:03.800 --> 00:39:09.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but there the issue is that the post that the judge already holds is the reward,

00:39:09.600 --> 00:39:13.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, being a judge on the Supreme Court, it's not as if they will do something with

00:39:13.080 --> 00:39:17.720
[Amit Varma]: the expectation of reward after it, they've already got the reward, and they can be an

00:39:17.720 --> 00:39:20.720
[Amit Varma]: implicit or explicit quid pro quo involved for that.

00:39:20.720 --> 00:39:22.720
[Guest]: So you know, that's the end.

00:39:22.720 --> 00:39:24.880
[Guest]: No one can hold you to it, right?

00:39:24.880 --> 00:39:30.200
[Guest]: Like, let's say there were a whole group of like unsavory people who got me elected to

00:39:30.200 --> 00:39:33.400
[Unknown]: the bench, right, or appointed to the bench.

00:39:33.400 --> 00:39:38.440
[Guest]: Now, because it's a life term appointment, I mean, if I choose to write what I choose

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:41.640
[Guest]: to write, so be it like they can't do anything after that.

00:39:41.640 --> 00:39:45.800
[Guest]: Right, they can't do anything to influence me after that, after that, I'm sort of in

00:39:45.800 --> 00:39:46.800
[Guest]: a bubble.

00:39:46.800 --> 00:39:52.520
[Guest]: Now, it just so happens that the vetting process is so detailed, they pull out law review articles

00:39:52.520 --> 00:39:55.760
[Guest]: and op-eds you wrote when you were 19 years old.

00:39:55.760 --> 00:40:02.000
[Guest]: And they're very, very, very careful that you hold the views that you say you hold.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:07.240
[Guest]: Having said that, if they appoint someone to the Supreme Court bench at age 45 or 50,

00:40:07.240 --> 00:40:11.120
[Guest]: and it's a life appointment, and you're on the bench for the next 40 years, who says

00:40:11.120 --> 00:40:13.360
[Guest]: you can't change your mind?

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:15.960
[Guest]: You know, who says you can't change your mind the very next day?

00:40:15.960 --> 00:40:18.960
[Guest]: Now, the Indian Supreme Court works a little bit differently.

00:40:18.960 --> 00:40:25.240
[Guest]: The retirement age was 65, because at the time of the founding of the country, the life

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:27.480
[Guest]: expectancy wasn't that high.

00:40:27.480 --> 00:40:33.820
[Guest]: But today, 65 is a very low retirement age, given that life expectancy has increased.

00:40:33.820 --> 00:40:39.040
[Guest]: So what's happening is most Supreme Court judges take on some role immediately after

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:43.040
[Guest]: they retire from the Supreme Court, and it typically tends to be government tribunals

00:40:43.040 --> 00:40:44.560
[Guest]: and panels.

00:40:44.560 --> 00:40:47.840
[Guest]: And guess who appoints people to the government tribunal and panels?

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:49.640
[Guest]: It's the executive.

00:40:49.640 --> 00:40:56.000
[Guest]: So now you have this very big problem of post-judicial appointments.

00:40:56.000 --> 00:41:01.280
[Guest]: And there has been some very interesting research on this particular issue.

00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:06.000
[Guest]: So I know we're reading a little bit of what we were talking about just a minute ago.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:14.400
[Guest]: But I want to emphasize that appointment procedure is not the only way to be independent.

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:18.360
[Guest]: There are other important ways to be independent, which is what is the salary that is given

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:22.920
[Guest]: to a judge, which is whether judges are transferred between high courts, which doesn't happen

00:41:22.920 --> 00:41:23.920
[Guest]: in America.

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:24.920
[Guest]: Right?

00:41:24.920 --> 00:41:29.600
[Guest]: I mean, every state is its own sort of like contained unit.

00:41:29.600 --> 00:41:32.760
[Guest]: You're not transferring judges from one state to another.

00:41:32.760 --> 00:41:34.920
[Guest]: So that is another kind of mechanism.

00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:36.600
[Guest]: And it's a lifetime appointment.

00:41:36.600 --> 00:41:43.240
[Guest]: So a couple of years ago, Madhav Ane, Shubhankar Dam and Giovanni Koh, they actually looked

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:50.840
[Guest]: at post-retirement appointments of Supreme Court judges and compared them to whether

00:41:50.840 --> 00:41:56.040
[Guest]: these judges authored favorable judgments in important cases just before they retired.

00:41:56.040 --> 00:41:57.040
[Guest]: And guess what they find?

00:41:57.040 --> 00:42:01.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'd imagine the incentives play out as you'd expect them to play out, right?

00:42:01.320 --> 00:42:02.320
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:42:02.320 --> 00:42:07.200
[Guest]: They actually write favorable judgments because Supreme Court justices are also human.

00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:14.080
[Guest]: They want a nice house in, you know, Abdul Kalam Road with a car with a red light on

00:42:14.080 --> 00:42:18.160
[Guest]: it and a whole staff and all the perks that come with it.

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:23.800
[Guest]: And they're basically fitted on this tribunal or that tribunal, you know, Election Commission,

00:42:23.800 --> 00:42:27.700
[Guest]: Right to Information Commission, this office, that office, there's a whole host of appointments

00:42:27.700 --> 00:42:28.700
[Guest]: that is possible.

00:42:28.700 --> 00:42:33.500
[Guest]: It makes a significant difference to the pay and the lifestyle of these justices.

00:42:33.500 --> 00:42:40.200
[Guest]: So while all the focus has been on appointment procedure alone, that is not the only way

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:41.200
[Guest]: to be independent.

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:47.360
[Guest]: We have managed to create a very pliant judiciary even when the appointment procedure is not

00:42:47.360 --> 00:42:49.560
[Guest]: interfered with, right?

00:42:49.560 --> 00:42:53.000
[Guest]: By post-retirement carrots, so to speak.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:56.360
[Guest]: So there are many differences and there are many ways to skin this cat.

00:42:56.360 --> 00:43:04.120
[Guest]: So if you think about it, the U.S. Supreme Court has nominees are appointed by the executive,

00:43:04.120 --> 00:43:09.680
[Guest]: but they are vetted by the legislature, which is you need a Senate confirmation hearing,

00:43:09.680 --> 00:43:10.680
[Guest]: right?

00:43:10.680 --> 00:43:13.800
[Guest]: So that is highly political process.

00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:18.640
[Guest]: It is not at all independent, but somehow it manages to protect the independence of

00:43:18.640 --> 00:43:23.960
[Guest]: the judge once the judge is on the bench and becomes a Supreme Court justice, right?

00:43:23.960 --> 00:43:30.520
[Guest]: So you can have a very political process and that still ensures independence, or you can

00:43:30.520 --> 00:43:35.680
[Guest]: have a very insular process, which is completely separate from the politics and still have

00:43:35.680 --> 00:43:38.760
[Guest]: a not so independent system.

00:43:38.760 --> 00:43:44.520
[Amit Varma]: So in fact, looking at our system, it would actually be remarkable to me if our judiciary

00:43:44.520 --> 00:43:46.120
[Amit Varma]: was independent.

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:51.960
[Amit Varma]: It seems it's designed to set up a dependence of the judiciary on the executive.

00:43:51.960 --> 00:43:52.960
[Amit Varma]: What do you think?

00:43:52.960 --> 00:43:56.760
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sure this has been discussed massively over the last few decades.

00:43:56.760 --> 00:44:03.280
[Amit Varma]: So what are the kind of steps that could have been taken or could be taken to make independence

00:44:03.280 --> 00:44:05.600
[Amit Varma]: more likely?

00:44:05.600 --> 00:44:10.120
[Guest]: So again, I want to take you back a little bit to the history of what happened, you know,

00:44:10.120 --> 00:44:16.520
[Guest]: so post Indira Gandhi's actions in the 70s and the horror of the emergency, transferring

00:44:16.520 --> 00:44:23.280
[Guest]: so many judges during the emergency really became like a farce, what was going on.

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:27.960
[Guest]: The legal community thought that it needs to do something, right?

00:44:27.960 --> 00:44:33.160
[Guest]: So there were a series of challenges on appointment procedure, because, you know, it became very

00:44:33.160 --> 00:44:37.560
[Guest]: clear that the appointment and the transfer procedure is not very clear and we need to

00:44:37.560 --> 00:44:39.320
[Guest]: come up with something.

00:44:39.320 --> 00:44:43.400
[Guest]: So the first of these cases is called the first judges case.

00:44:43.400 --> 00:44:46.840
[Guest]: It was in 1982, S.P. Gupta versus Union of India.

00:44:46.840 --> 00:44:52.560
[Guest]: And in this particular case, the court was asked, so exactly what does this consultative

00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:54.720
[Guest]: process mean, right?

00:44:54.720 --> 00:45:00.680
[Guest]: So the court simply said that it limited the unfettered power of the executive, right?

00:45:00.680 --> 00:45:07.960
[Guest]: The consultation should be full, the chief justice's opinion must be recorded, it must

00:45:07.960 --> 00:45:11.920
[Guest]: be considered, it can't be easily disregarded.

00:45:11.920 --> 00:45:16.120
[Guest]: Having said that, the chief justice of India's opinion on appointments and transfers is not

00:45:16.120 --> 00:45:17.120
[Guest]: binding.

00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:18.120
[Guest]: Right?

00:45:18.120 --> 00:45:19.120
[Guest]: So that was the first judges case.

00:45:19.120 --> 00:45:24.560
[Guest]: Now, this is a very traditional interpretation because nowhere in the constitution does it

00:45:24.560 --> 00:45:28.920
[Guest]: seem to suggest that the judiciary's opinion on appointments should be binding.

00:45:28.920 --> 00:45:34.440
[Guest]: So in a sense, even in the 1980s, the Supreme Court justices were not very activist and

00:45:34.440 --> 00:45:38.280
[Guest]: still conservative and they were interpreting the text of the constitution.

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:44.360
[Guest]: But as we know, since the 80s, after post-emergency, there was like a two-year Janata government

00:45:44.360 --> 00:45:45.360
[Guest]: period.

00:45:45.360 --> 00:45:47.440
[Guest]: And then after that, it was back to politics as usual.

00:45:47.440 --> 00:45:50.880
[Guest]: So all the usual shenanigans started.

00:45:50.880 --> 00:45:54.400
[Guest]: And there was a really important question of how do we really protect the independence

00:45:54.400 --> 00:45:55.800
[Guest]: of judges?

00:45:55.800 --> 00:45:59.480
[Guest]: And this brings me to the second judges case, right?

00:45:59.480 --> 00:46:05.980
[Guest]: This was a case in 93, and it was basically the legal community, the Supreme Court's advocates

00:46:05.980 --> 00:46:13.760
[Guest]: on record who questioned once again, the existing procedure in articles 124, 217, and 222, right?

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:16.400
[Guest]: And they said, there are poor procedural safeguards.

00:46:16.400 --> 00:46:18.360
[Guest]: So what do we do now?

00:46:18.360 --> 00:46:23.640
[Guest]: This is perhaps the most activist judicial opinion written, not just by the Supreme Court

00:46:23.640 --> 00:46:27.320
[Guest]: of India, but any court anywhere in the world, right?

00:46:27.320 --> 00:46:31.880
[Guest]: They basically created a new procedure to appoint Supreme Court and high court judges

00:46:31.880 --> 00:46:33.920
[Guest]: out of thin air.

00:46:33.920 --> 00:46:37.560
[Guest]: And if you compare the procedure to what is the text of the constitution, you will think

00:46:37.560 --> 00:46:40.480
[Guest]: you are in two different countries and the pages got mixed up.

00:46:40.480 --> 00:46:41.480
[Guest]: Okay.

00:46:41.480 --> 00:46:46.280
[Guest]: So what they did was they said, we're going to create a collegium system.

00:46:46.280 --> 00:46:52.680
[Guest]: The collegium is led by the Supreme Court of India and two of the senior most judges.

00:46:52.680 --> 00:46:58.600
[Guest]: And these three people will come up with a list of who needs to be appointed and who

00:46:58.600 --> 00:47:00.280
[Guest]: needs to be transferred.

00:47:00.280 --> 00:47:05.960
[Guest]: And they will give this list to the cabinet or the president who actually, in whose name

00:47:05.960 --> 00:47:11.720
[Guest]: the appointments are made and their recommendations are binding and they cannot be violated.

00:47:11.720 --> 00:47:12.720
[Guest]: Okay.

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:17.800
[Guest]: Now, as you can see, this is a drastically different system from what was actually written

00:47:17.800 --> 00:47:19.720
[Guest]: in text.

00:47:19.720 --> 00:47:23.120
[Guest]: Some people thought this was the most amazing thing that had ever happened.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:28.780
[Guest]: And the judiciary had finally come of age and declared its own independence.

00:47:28.780 --> 00:47:34.400
[Guest]: Many others felt that this is outrageous and very self-serving activism.

00:47:34.400 --> 00:47:39.160
[Guest]: And this is going to create a situation where there is no external scrutiny or check on

00:47:39.160 --> 00:47:40.160
[Guest]: the judiciary.

00:47:40.160 --> 00:47:44.000
[Guest]: And it's basically a self-appointing system, right?

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:49.160
[Guest]: Only the current chief justice of India determines who are the next people who rise to the bench.

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:51.160
[Guest]: So it's extremely problematic.

00:47:51.160 --> 00:47:54.000
[Guest]: A presidential reference was made in 1998.

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:59.080
[Guest]: The president of India can ask the Supreme Court to clarify on matters of law or national

00:47:59.080 --> 00:48:00.720
[Guest]: importance and so on.

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:07.680
[Guest]: And this presidential reference in 1998, again, the court put in a few more safeguards to

00:48:07.680 --> 00:48:08.680
[Guest]: this collegium system.

00:48:08.680 --> 00:48:10.080
[Guest]: So it's called the third judge's case.

00:48:10.080 --> 00:48:12.960
[Guest]: So they added some more safeguards to the second judge's case.

00:48:12.960 --> 00:48:16.440
[Guest]: They said that, you know, the collegium must meet and the minutes must be recorded.

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:18.580
[Guest]: It must be a transparent system.

00:48:18.580 --> 00:48:22.800
[Guest]: And the collegium is going to be not this chief justice of India plus two judges, but

00:48:22.800 --> 00:48:25.980
[Guest]: chief justice of India and the next four senior most judges.

00:48:25.980 --> 00:48:28.880
[Guest]: So the collegium will have five people, right?

00:48:28.880 --> 00:48:34.120
[Guest]: And this will be the group that determines who is appointed and who will be promoted

00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:36.160
[Guest]: to the Supreme Court and so on.

00:48:36.160 --> 00:48:41.760
[Guest]: And they will give their list to cabinet and the president will make these appointments.

00:48:41.760 --> 00:48:46.520
[Guest]: Now once again, coming to the importance of convention, when all this was happening in

00:48:46.520 --> 00:48:52.360
[Guest]: 1998, you can imagine that if it had been Indira Gandhi, who was the prime minister,

00:48:52.360 --> 00:48:56.120
[Guest]: she would have just shut the whole thing down, right?

00:48:56.120 --> 00:49:02.200
[Guest]: But it just so happened that people who had lived through the emergency and, you know,

00:49:02.200 --> 00:49:07.120
[Guest]: better, more statesmen leaders were beginning to come to power.

00:49:07.120 --> 00:49:11.240
[Guest]: And immediately after that is the time of Vajpayee, right?

00:49:11.240 --> 00:49:15.400
[Guest]: And it seems to be quite clear that everyone in the executive thought that this is a very

00:49:15.400 --> 00:49:21.160
[Guest]: bad idea, but they shouldn't mess with the independence of the judiciary.

00:49:21.160 --> 00:49:24.960
[Guest]: And they should respect this opinion, right?

00:49:24.960 --> 00:49:27.160
[Guest]: So presidential reference was made.

00:49:27.160 --> 00:49:30.600
[Guest]: Once the Supreme Court clarified the matter, the matter was left alone.

00:49:30.600 --> 00:49:38.760
[Guest]: So from 1993 until 2015, we had a second system of appointments, which was by collegium.

00:49:38.760 --> 00:49:44.040
[Guest]: And before that, you know, from 1951 to 1993 was the first system of appointments, which

00:49:44.040 --> 00:49:45.840
[Guest]: was by consultation, right?

00:49:45.840 --> 00:49:48.600
[Guest]: Aside from the shenanigans of Indira Gandhi.

00:49:48.600 --> 00:49:50.920
[Guest]: So this was really what was going on.

00:49:50.920 --> 00:49:57.720
[Guest]: Now you don't need much of a legal education to guess what would happen in a system like

00:49:57.720 --> 00:49:58.720
[Guest]: this.

00:49:58.720 --> 00:50:04.600
[Guest]: So, you know, the usual, which is nepotism, which is not the most qualified people rising

00:50:04.600 --> 00:50:07.960
[Guest]: to the bench, but people who have connections, right?

00:50:07.960 --> 00:50:14.000
[Guest]: So if you have served and you had on good relationships with the sort of like the elite

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:21.960
[Guest]: judicial coterie, then you are promoted, a lot of children and grandchildren and siblings

00:50:21.960 --> 00:50:25.840
[Guest]: of past justices were promoted and they rose to the top.

00:50:25.840 --> 00:50:31.360
[Guest]: And some internal corruption really started setting into the court system.

00:50:31.360 --> 00:50:35.720
[Guest]: So there was a time when the court system was really beyond reproach.

00:50:35.720 --> 00:50:40.280
[Guest]: You know, giants had served on the court and they were really, they held themselves to

00:50:40.280 --> 00:50:43.480
[Guest]: such a high standard and never put a foot out of place.

00:50:43.480 --> 00:50:49.160
[Guest]: And it was really important that they not only did what is right, but also seemed to

00:50:49.160 --> 00:50:52.480
[Guest]: do what is right, which is, you know, hold themselves to a higher standard.

00:50:52.480 --> 00:50:57.080
[Guest]: Now, all of them that started disappearing under the collegium system and it became quite

00:50:57.080 --> 00:51:02.680
[Guest]: clear that the Supreme Court and all the judges were a little bit like, you know, power drunk

00:51:02.680 --> 00:51:05.000
[Guest]: and they thought they could do whatever they wanted.

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:09.520
[Guest]: This is, you know, the eighties, nineties, and since the 2000s, especially the nineties

00:51:09.520 --> 00:51:14.440
[Guest]: and the 2000s is also the most activist form of the judiciary.

00:51:14.440 --> 00:51:19.800
[Guest]: So the Supreme Court butts its head into every policy matter.

00:51:19.800 --> 00:51:24.240
[Guest]: It is legislating from the bench, it passes daily orders on all matters from taxation,

00:51:24.240 --> 00:51:30.260
[Guest]: which was never under its purview to the powers of pretty much every other institution, right?

00:51:30.260 --> 00:51:37.560
[Guest]: So the Supreme Court has become its own powerful giant and this entire, you know, sort of jugglery

00:51:37.560 --> 00:51:42.200
[Guest]: trick worked because the people had a lot of faith in the institution.

00:51:42.200 --> 00:51:45.880
[Guest]: So as long as the public supports you, in a sense, you can sort of get away with a lot

00:51:45.880 --> 00:51:48.880
[Guest]: of procedural problems, right?

00:51:48.880 --> 00:51:53.600
[Guest]: So the people of India thought the Supreme Court is this hallowed institution and that's

00:51:53.600 --> 00:51:58.480
[Guest]: really where we get justice through specially petitions and public interest litigations

00:51:58.480 --> 00:51:59.800
[Guest]: and all of those things.

00:51:59.800 --> 00:52:03.420
[Guest]: And it seems to be the last uncorrupted bastion.

00:52:03.420 --> 00:52:07.800
[Guest]: So the Supreme Court got away with this for a long time.

00:52:07.800 --> 00:52:12.800
[Guest]: And then once the corruption started becoming more and more public is when, you know, sort

00:52:12.800 --> 00:52:15.360
[Guest]: of the music stopped and you had to take stock.

00:52:15.360 --> 00:52:19.560
[Amit Varma]: So before we go to that part of the story, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:52:19.560 --> 00:52:25.560
[Amit Varma]: And then when we come back, I also want to ask you more about the activism of the court,

00:52:25.560 --> 00:52:27.360
[Amit Varma]: the legislating from the bench, so to speak.

00:52:27.360 --> 00:52:34.360
[Unknown]: But first, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:53:58.360 --> 00:54:00.480
[Unknown]: So, welcome back to India's Gram Sabhas, one of India's biggest democratic successes since

