[Unknown]: And with that, let's go on with your show.

00:54:28.260 --> 00:54:29.540
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

00:54:29.540 --> 00:54:34.420
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Shruti Rajgopalan about the state of our judiciary.

00:54:34.420 --> 00:54:38.380
[Amit Varma]: And my next question following on from what you were speaking about before the break is

00:54:38.380 --> 00:54:40.180
[Amit Varma]: really about judicial activism.

00:54:40.180 --> 00:54:44.380
[Amit Varma]: I mean, forgive the newbie question, but my impression of the judiciary always was that

00:54:44.380 --> 00:54:50.100
[Amit Varma]: look, the judges are basically supposed to interpret what the laws are or what the Constitution

00:54:50.100 --> 00:54:53.260
[Amit Varma]: says and their judgments are on the basis of that.

00:54:53.260 --> 00:54:58.260
[Amit Varma]: Their own opinions don't really matter, they can't, to use that phrase, legislate from

00:54:58.260 --> 00:54:59.260
[Amit Varma]: the bench.

00:54:59.260 --> 00:55:01.220
[Amit Varma]: It's the job of the legislature to legislate.

00:55:01.220 --> 00:55:06.340
[Amit Varma]: And what the Supreme Court simply does is that it interprets existing laws and the Constitution

00:55:06.340 --> 00:55:08.340
[Amit Varma]: and pass the judgments based on that.

00:55:08.340 --> 00:55:14.480
[Amit Varma]: Now, a number of the judgments that we've spoken about in this episode, whether it's,

00:55:14.480 --> 00:55:18.180
[Amit Varma]: for example, the basic structure judgment, where I wonder on the basis of what do they

00:55:18.180 --> 00:55:22.300
[Amit Varma]: decide what the basic structure is of the Constitution doesn't mention that, or the

00:55:22.300 --> 00:55:27.460
[Amit Varma]: 1993 second judge's case, where they decide that there should be a collegium and this

00:55:27.460 --> 00:55:32.140
[Amit Varma]: is a procedure and blah, blah, blah, on the basis of what do they decide that or even

00:55:32.140 --> 00:55:37.740
[Amit Varma]: the Vishakha judgment, which both of us agree is excellent and a really positive move forward.

00:55:37.740 --> 00:55:41.900
[Amit Varma]: But on the basis of what do they arrive at something, because the point is that once

00:55:41.900 --> 00:55:47.660
[Amit Varma]: you accept that the judges have a right to sort of legislate from the bench as it were,

00:55:47.660 --> 00:55:52.500
[Amit Varma]: then depending on which people are on the bench, they can legislate absolutely anything,

00:55:52.500 --> 00:55:53.500
[Amit Varma]: right?

00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:54.500
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:55:54.500 --> 00:55:57.460
[Guest]: So, you know, there are two, three different views on this.

00:55:57.460 --> 00:56:01.820
[Guest]: And I finally come to the point that no matter which view you take, the Indian Supreme Court

00:56:01.820 --> 00:56:03.780
[Guest]: is still doing the wrong thing.

00:56:03.780 --> 00:56:04.780
[Guest]: Okay.

00:56:04.780 --> 00:56:11.540
[Guest]: So the first view is, look, it is always the job of the court to be conservative and not

00:56:11.540 --> 00:56:12.540
[Guest]: activist.

00:56:12.540 --> 00:56:14.260
[Guest]: And what do we mean by activists?

00:56:14.260 --> 00:56:19.320
[Guest]: Now there are two ways to think about the role of the judiciary, right?

00:56:19.320 --> 00:56:22.560
[Guest]: So the first is it provides a check and balance.

00:56:22.560 --> 00:56:27.340
[Guest]: So you know, whatever the executive and the legislature do to preserve principles of natural

00:56:27.340 --> 00:56:32.220
[Guest]: justice and the spirit of the constitution, you need to provide a valid check.

00:56:32.220 --> 00:56:37.300
[Guest]: Now, based on this kind of interpretation, if your legislature and executive are going

00:56:37.300 --> 00:56:42.200
[Guest]: bonkers, it means your judiciary can go bonkers, right?

00:56:42.200 --> 00:56:47.460
[Guest]: So if you have a legislature, which is repeatedly amends the constitution, then you're going

00:56:47.460 --> 00:56:55.860
[Guest]: to end up placing the judiciary in a situation where they may also have to exceed their powers

00:56:55.860 --> 00:57:01.380
[Guest]: a little bit or their original powers a little bit, or get more creative with their interpretation

00:57:01.380 --> 00:57:05.940
[Guest]: to actually give a solid check to the legislature and the executive.

00:57:05.940 --> 00:57:12.620
[Guest]: So this kind of activism, most legal scholars are quite comfortable with in the sense that

00:57:12.620 --> 00:57:19.500
[Guest]: they feel that the job of the judiciary is to really pursue in a very spirited way, really

00:57:19.500 --> 00:57:23.820
[Guest]: pursue the protection of individual rights and the constitution.

00:57:23.820 --> 00:57:29.700
[Guest]: So in this sense, a lot of the activism that happens during the emergency, you know, like

00:57:29.700 --> 00:57:37.180
[Guest]: Justice HR Khanna's opinion in Keshavanand Bharti or Jabalpur versus ADM Shivkanth Shukla.

00:57:37.180 --> 00:57:42.280
[Guest]: These are all legendary cases where there could have been a textbook interpretation

00:57:42.280 --> 00:57:45.980
[Guest]: and they went a step ahead of the textbook interpretation.

00:57:45.980 --> 00:57:50.420
[Guest]: But the goal was still to protect individual rights and it wasn't self-serving in the sense

00:57:50.420 --> 00:57:52.700
[Guest]: that it wasn't increasing the power of the judiciary.

00:57:52.700 --> 00:57:56.900
[Amit Varma]: So basically by the spirit of the book, if not the actual words, because the actual words

00:57:56.900 --> 00:57:59.020
[Guest]: can be changed at any point.

00:57:59.020 --> 00:58:00.020
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:58:00.020 --> 00:58:02.620
[Guest]: Now there's another version of what is the role of the judiciary.

00:58:02.620 --> 00:58:04.180
[Guest]: So first is checks and balances, right?

00:58:04.180 --> 00:58:10.380
[Guest]: The second part of it is a very Adam Smith division of labor kind of view of the judiciary.

00:58:10.380 --> 00:58:14.780
[Guest]: In fact, Adam Smith writes about this in The Wealth of Nations, that there are two roles.

00:58:14.780 --> 00:58:19.260
[Guest]: One is the functional task, which is, you know, the judiciary's job is really to go

00:58:19.260 --> 00:58:23.580
[Guest]: through a lot of evidence procedure and actually adjudicate.

00:58:23.580 --> 00:58:26.580
[Guest]: And that's a highly specialized task, right?

00:58:26.580 --> 00:58:31.420
[Guest]: The legislature's job is to amalgamate preferences of millions of people.

00:58:31.420 --> 00:58:33.300
[Guest]: And that's the legislature's job.

00:58:33.300 --> 00:58:40.260
[Guest]: The executive's job is to execute the goals of the government, you know, as conveyed by

00:58:40.260 --> 00:58:42.900
[Guest]: the legislature or the preferences of the people.

00:58:42.900 --> 00:58:45.940
[Guest]: So these are three very fundamentally different tasks.

00:58:45.940 --> 00:58:51.760
[Guest]: You know, this is as different as the butcher, the brewer and the baker.

00:58:51.760 --> 00:58:58.540
[Guest]: So in that sense, the one way to think about judicial activism is you're really doing jobs

00:58:58.540 --> 00:59:04.180
[Guest]: which are outside your expertise and outside your purview, which is why you must be limited.

00:59:04.180 --> 00:59:10.380
[Guest]: So you know, things like fiscal matters, about taxation, about government spending, about,

00:59:10.380 --> 00:59:12.740
[Guest]: you know, I'll give you a good example of this.

00:59:12.740 --> 00:59:15.420
[Guest]: Now think of the CNG cases.

00:59:15.420 --> 00:59:20.740
[Guest]: Do you remember when they changed all the fleet of buses in Delhi and then eventually

00:59:20.740 --> 00:59:24.540
[Guest]: in other states from diesel to CNG?

00:59:24.540 --> 00:59:25.540
[Amit Varma]: Do you have any?

00:59:25.540 --> 00:59:26.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I remember this.

00:59:26.540 --> 00:59:27.540
[Amit Varma]: It happened.

00:59:27.540 --> 00:59:28.540
[Amit Varma]: I am fairly old.

00:59:28.540 --> 00:59:29.540
[Amit Varma]: So this happened in the early 2000s.

00:59:29.540 --> 00:59:30.540
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:59:30.540 --> 00:59:32.940
[Guest]: No, but I mean, you're also not from Delhi.

00:59:32.940 --> 00:59:35.780
[Guest]: So you know, you may have not really lived through it.

00:59:35.780 --> 00:59:40.100
[Guest]: So this was when the early 2000s, I was in high school, just starting college.

00:59:40.100 --> 00:59:46.180
[Guest]: Overnight, the court just, you know, there were a series of cases by MC Mehta, who was

00:59:46.180 --> 00:59:47.940
[Guest]: sort of like this environmental activist.

00:59:47.940 --> 00:59:51.460
[Guest]: And he said, you know, people of Delhi can't breathe, and you can imagine he said this

00:59:51.460 --> 00:59:52.460
[Guest]: like 20 years ago.

00:59:52.460 --> 00:59:53.460
[Guest]: Right.

00:59:53.460 --> 00:59:54.460
[Guest]: Can you imagine what they would say today?

00:59:54.460 --> 00:59:59.900
[Guest]: They said the biggest problem is all the particulate matter that comes out of these diesel buses.

00:59:59.900 --> 01:00:04.020
[Guest]: We need to make sure that all the diesel buses change to CNG overnight.

01:00:04.020 --> 01:00:05.020
[Guest]: Okay.

01:00:05.020 --> 01:00:09.940
[Guest]: Now think about what it takes to change an entire fleet of government and private buses.

01:00:09.940 --> 01:00:10.940
[Guest]: You need an infrastructure.

01:00:10.940 --> 01:00:13.660
[Guest]: First of all, these buses need to exist.

01:00:13.660 --> 01:00:16.340
[Guest]: Then you need to refit them.

01:00:16.340 --> 01:00:23.340
[Guest]: Once you refit them, every petrol pump in the city needs to outfit itself with a CNG

01:00:23.340 --> 01:00:24.340
[Guest]: station.

01:00:24.340 --> 01:00:25.340
[Guest]: Right.

01:00:25.340 --> 01:00:30.140
[Guest]: Now, the court simply said, change 10,000 buses to CNG.

01:00:30.140 --> 01:00:31.720
[Guest]: They gave them a deadline.

01:00:31.720 --> 01:00:33.420
[Guest]: The Delhi government violated the deadline.

01:00:33.420 --> 01:00:36.020
[Guest]: They gave them a second deadline, the Delhi government violated the deadline.

01:00:36.020 --> 01:00:41.780
[Guest]: Supreme Court got so sick of the Delhi government, they just said, diesel buses cannot fly after

01:00:41.780 --> 01:00:43.700
[Guest]: such and such date.

01:00:43.700 --> 01:00:46.460
[Guest]: And overnight it was like a Soviet Union.

01:00:46.460 --> 01:00:47.460
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:00:47.460 --> 01:00:53.700
[Guest]: I mean, there were no buses and all the autos and buses, we, even the ones that had CNG,

01:00:53.700 --> 01:00:59.620
[Guest]: the lines outside the petrol stations and the CNG stations were, I mean, you really

01:00:59.620 --> 01:01:02.820
[Guest]: thought you're living in a shortage Soviet style economy.

01:01:02.820 --> 01:01:09.820
[Guest]: Like these four auto rickshaw and bus drivers would stand in line for three or four days

01:01:09.820 --> 01:01:13.500
[Guest]: to get one tank full of CNG and then continue again.

01:01:13.500 --> 01:01:18.820
[Guest]: So now if you think about this from the point of view of the, you know, functional separation

01:01:18.820 --> 01:01:24.020
[Guest]: of powers, not just the checks and balances, this is about specialization and knowledge,

01:01:24.020 --> 01:01:25.020
[Guest]: right?

01:01:25.020 --> 01:01:29.740
[Guest]: The courts, which basically adjudicate disputes, which are over a matter of fact or matter

01:01:29.740 --> 01:01:35.900
[Guest]: of law, they simply don't know how to execute a transition from system A to system B, which

01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:37.940
[Guest]: is a question of governance.

01:01:37.940 --> 01:01:40.780
[Guest]: That is squarely in the pocket of the executive.

01:01:40.780 --> 01:01:45.140
[Guest]: The court said, Oh, we didn't know that, you know, there will be the CNG problem.

01:01:45.140 --> 01:01:47.580
[Guest]: It's like a classic knowledge problem, right?

01:01:47.580 --> 01:01:51.860
[Guest]: Of course you can overnight convert and say the buses are going to run on CNG, but you

01:01:51.860 --> 01:01:57.180
[Guest]: can't produce CNG out of thin air and make it available exactly where the people need

01:01:57.180 --> 01:01:58.620
[Guest]: it to be available.

01:01:58.620 --> 01:02:03.580
[Guest]: This would have required the Delhi state government issuing new licenses to all the petrol pumps,

01:02:03.580 --> 01:02:05.060
[Guest]: creating new petrol pumps with CNG.

01:02:05.060 --> 01:02:08.860
[Guest]: You know, it's a whole infrastructure that takes place and the government knew about

01:02:08.860 --> 01:02:09.860
[Guest]: it.

01:02:09.860 --> 01:02:13.820
[Guest]: And it's so funny that the Supreme Court justices who are very smart people didn't know about

01:02:13.820 --> 01:02:17.420
[Guest]: it because it's simply not within their purview to know this.

01:02:17.420 --> 01:02:22.540
[Guest]: On the second matter, which is this question of, you know, the functional knowledge to

01:02:22.540 --> 01:02:28.980
[Guest]: execute on some of these tasks, those are the more like very problematic questions of

01:02:28.980 --> 01:02:31.500
[Guest]: judicial interference or judicial activism.

01:02:31.500 --> 01:02:34.180
[Guest]: You have ludicrous examples of this.

01:02:34.180 --> 01:02:40.140
[Guest]: So the Delhi High Court at one point was trying to legislate or standardize the height of

01:02:40.140 --> 01:02:42.460
[Guest]: speed breakers in Delhi.

01:02:42.460 --> 01:02:46.500
[Guest]: Is it really the job of the courts to decide what the height of speed breakers is?

01:02:46.500 --> 01:02:49.060
[Guest]: And I'll tell you how the matter came about.

01:02:49.060 --> 01:02:53.900
[Guest]: Resident welfare associations were randomly building speed breakers near schools or in

01:02:53.900 --> 01:02:56.860
[Guest]: front of their house to reduce the number of accidents, right?

01:02:56.860 --> 01:03:02.180
[Guest]: Because we have such poor sort of traffic rule following spirit in India.

01:03:02.180 --> 01:03:07.140
[Guest]: So people were doing all this and they realized that all the speed breakers are of uneven

01:03:07.140 --> 01:03:10.940
[Guest]: heights, which apparently is a matter of national importance.

01:03:10.940 --> 01:03:15.100
[Guest]: Someone filed a public interest litigation and the public interest litigation now decided

01:03:15.100 --> 01:03:20.780
[Guest]: whether or not you can have speed breakers and how high these speed breakers should be.

01:03:20.780 --> 01:03:25.380
[Guest]: And you think about it and you're like, really, the pendency of cases is extraordinary at

01:03:25.380 --> 01:03:26.380
[Guest]: this point.

01:03:26.380 --> 01:03:32.140
[Guest]: There are people in jail who are being deprived of their rights because the cases are going

01:03:32.140 --> 01:03:33.140
[Guest]: on for too long.

01:03:33.140 --> 01:03:37.860
[Guest]: There are land dispute cases where the original parties to the case have died waiting for

01:03:37.860 --> 01:03:38.860
[Guest]: justice.

01:03:38.860 --> 01:03:43.460
[Guest]: And the Supreme Court thinks that the most important thing is to legislate from the bench

01:03:43.460 --> 01:03:49.740
[Guest]: on CNG and the, you know, Delhi Bird Sanctuary and the air quality and the height of speed

01:03:49.740 --> 01:03:50.740
[Guest]: breakers.

01:03:50.740 --> 01:03:53.900
[Guest]: And this list has become extremely long.

01:03:53.900 --> 01:03:59.300
[Guest]: There is virtually no area of Indian governance where the Supreme Court has not given its

01:03:59.300 --> 01:04:01.100
[Guest]: opinion one way or another.

01:04:01.100 --> 01:04:05.540
[Amit Varma]: I'm having this very funny image of Supreme Court judges in their black robes measuring

01:04:05.540 --> 01:04:11.580
[Amit Varma]: the height of speed breakers on Delhi streets as CNG autos whizz by and a classic example

01:04:11.580 --> 01:04:16.340
[Amit Varma]: of this in a domain which I know fairly well is the interference of the Supreme Court and

01:04:16.340 --> 01:04:19.580
[Amit Varma]: the BCCI in Indian cricket.

01:04:19.580 --> 01:04:24.940
[Amit Varma]: What the COA is doing where they're completely clueless about how to run Indian cricket and

01:04:24.940 --> 01:04:28.780
[Amit Varma]: I don't even know whether they actually have the jurisdiction to interfere in the way they

01:04:28.780 --> 01:04:31.220
[Amit Varma]: are, but that's a separate issue.

01:04:31.220 --> 01:04:32.220
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:04:32.220 --> 01:04:37.780
[Guest]: And it just so happened that, you know, the people of India are so tired of waiting for

01:04:37.780 --> 01:04:44.340
[Guest]: procedures and governance and they're so exhausted by executive inaction that they think they

01:04:44.340 --> 01:04:46.420
[Guest]: have no choice but to go to the court.

01:04:46.420 --> 01:04:50.060
[Guest]: I'll give you another example of activism in the Supreme Court.

01:04:50.060 --> 01:04:51.060
[Guest]: Okay.

01:04:51.060 --> 01:04:53.060
[Guest]: And how this activism can be very problematic.

01:04:53.060 --> 01:04:58.740
[Guest]: So one of the reasons that the activism started in the 1980s was as a social justice program,

01:04:58.740 --> 01:05:03.220
[Guest]: you know, bonded laborers, you know, this is a Badua Mukti Mocha case that came out

01:05:03.220 --> 01:05:05.620
[Guest]: of the mining community.

01:05:05.620 --> 01:05:12.780
[Guest]: They were like mine workers and bonded laborers who were just living like such a horror in

01:05:12.780 --> 01:05:15.100
[Guest]: their daily life and their workplace.

01:05:15.100 --> 01:05:18.940
[Guest]: And they didn't have much voice or agency, right?

01:05:18.940 --> 01:05:23.340
[Guest]: And through a series of cases, the court started interfering and actually assigning positive

01:05:23.340 --> 01:05:24.340
[Guest]: rights.

01:05:24.340 --> 01:05:28.820
[Guest]: And another very interesting thing that the Supreme Court did at the time was it reduced

01:05:28.820 --> 01:05:32.500
[Guest]: what is called the locus standi requirement, right?

01:05:32.500 --> 01:05:38.300
[Guest]: Normally in any court case, the parties to the case need to show that they have standing.

01:05:38.300 --> 01:05:42.620
[Guest]: You know, if you wanted to use a very contemporary economic term, it would be skin in the game,

01:05:42.620 --> 01:05:43.620
[Guest]: right?

01:05:43.620 --> 01:05:47.940
[Guest]: They have to show that they're actually affected parties in this particular dispute and that's

01:05:47.940 --> 01:05:49.620
[Guest]: why they're coming to court.

01:05:49.620 --> 01:05:53.420
[Guest]: Now the court said, you know, a lot of the people who are deprived of human rights, like

01:05:53.420 --> 01:05:58.420
[Guest]: children, like minorities, Dalits, bonded laborers, they really don't have the agency

01:05:58.420 --> 01:06:00.780
[Guest]: to come forward and represent themselves.

01:06:00.780 --> 01:06:05.580
[Guest]: So if a public interested or public spirited human being came to represent them, we will

01:06:05.580 --> 01:06:06.580
[Guest]: allow it.

01:06:06.580 --> 01:06:07.580
[Guest]: Right?

01:06:07.580 --> 01:06:09.660
[Guest]: Now you can imagine this is such a great thing, right?

01:06:09.660 --> 01:06:14.900
[Guest]: I mean, like diluting locus standing so that we can help slum dwellers and we can help

01:06:14.900 --> 01:06:20.980
[Guest]: bonded laborers seems like such a, it seems like activism, but the right kind of activism.

01:06:20.980 --> 01:06:24.220
[Guest]: Now let me explain the problem with this.

01:06:24.220 --> 01:06:29.300
[Guest]: Random people come out of the woodwork representing problems where they are not directly affected,

01:06:29.300 --> 01:06:30.300
[Guest]: right?

01:06:30.300 --> 01:06:34.820
[Guest]: And if you represent problems where you're not directly affected, one, there is an incentive

01:06:34.820 --> 01:06:38.140
[Guest]: problem, but there is also a knowledge problem.

01:06:38.140 --> 01:06:44.300
[Guest]: Delhi lawyers who live in elite Delhi areas and Delhi judges who don't take auto rickshaws

01:06:44.300 --> 01:06:49.940
[Guest]: and don't take buses are legislating on matters where they have no skin in the game and they

01:06:49.940 --> 01:06:52.900
[Guest]: have nothing to lose and everything to gain.

01:06:52.900 --> 01:06:56.080
[Guest]: And the other side parties end up being underrepresented.

01:06:56.080 --> 01:07:00.820
[Guest]: Now let me give you the worst example of diluting locus standard requirements.

01:07:00.820 --> 01:07:07.100
[Guest]: Now if you remember our entire journey in our country with section 377, originally the

01:07:07.100 --> 01:07:14.840
[Guest]: Delhi high court in the NAS foundation case had struck down 377 and upheld the right to

01:07:14.840 --> 01:07:18.140
[Guest]: same sex consensual relationships, right?

01:07:18.140 --> 01:07:20.320
[Guest]: This was a Delhi high court judgment.

01:07:20.320 --> 01:07:24.600
[Guest]: This court appealed to the Supreme court and the Supreme court overturned it, right?

01:07:24.600 --> 01:07:29.220
[Guest]: This was all the drama that took place before what happened last year.

01:07:29.220 --> 01:07:32.860
[Guest]: Now if you look at Supreme court overturning the Delhi high court case and you actually

01:07:32.860 --> 01:07:37.540
[Guest]: look into the matter, you'll notice that NAS foundation did not appeal the Delhi high court

01:07:37.540 --> 01:07:38.540
[Guest]: judgment.

01:07:38.540 --> 01:07:39.540
[Guest]: Okay.

01:07:39.540 --> 01:07:43.860
[Guest]: The government at the time, which was the UPA government and the Delhi government did

01:07:43.860 --> 01:07:46.420
[Guest]: not appeal the case, even though they lost.

01:07:46.420 --> 01:07:51.180
[Guest]: They said, you know, the courts have spoken, we leave it be, we are okay with 377 being

01:07:51.180 --> 01:07:52.940
[Guest]: struck down.

01:07:52.940 --> 01:07:58.980
[Guest]: The person who actually appealed the case was a Hindu astrologer.

01:07:58.980 --> 01:08:04.840
[Guest]: Second, this Hindu astrologer was not a party to the original suit.

01:08:04.840 --> 01:08:11.860
[Guest]: So it's like there are two, you know, teams playing cricket and now someone who was neither

01:08:11.860 --> 01:08:16.580
[Guest]: a player, nor the umpire, nor the spectator, but was, you know, standing and eating mangoes

01:08:16.580 --> 01:08:21.420
[Guest]: outside suddenly comes in and says, I think this game and its outcome was unfair.

01:08:21.420 --> 01:08:26.600
[Guest]: And the court heard it and they had to, because they are bound now by their own precedent

01:08:26.600 --> 01:08:28.900
[Guest]: of diluting standing requirements.

01:08:28.900 --> 01:08:32.420
[Guest]: And if anyone can come and appeal anything, guess what?

01:08:32.420 --> 01:08:34.940
[Guest]: Anyone will come and appeal anything.

01:08:34.940 --> 01:08:39.700
[Guest]: And that is so according to me, that Supreme court case was not just bad law, it was bad

01:08:39.700 --> 01:08:44.220
[Guest]: procedure because they just randomly allowed, you know, a third party who had nothing to

01:08:44.220 --> 01:08:49.620
[Guest]: do with the case to come in a little too late and they heard the appeal and then they overturned

01:08:49.620 --> 01:08:50.620
[Guest]: the case.

01:08:50.620 --> 01:08:55.300
[Guest]: So according to me, you know, all the activism of the Supreme court got in the way of all

01:08:55.300 --> 01:08:57.500
[Guest]: the activism of the Supreme court, right?

01:08:57.500 --> 01:09:01.940
[Guest]: This is the problem with having these terrible inconsistent set of rules and not binding

01:09:01.940 --> 01:09:03.700
[Guest]: yourself with procedure.

01:09:03.700 --> 01:09:08.460
[Guest]: So when you're asking broader question of judicial activism, some of it has held us

01:09:08.460 --> 01:09:15.040
[Guest]: in good stead because I have to say in a world where no other institution was really checking

01:09:15.040 --> 01:09:19.540
[Guest]: the power of the government, it was only the judiciary.

01:09:19.540 --> 01:09:24.340
[Guest]: Now the poor outcome of that is the judiciary grew too big for its own boots.

01:09:24.340 --> 01:09:29.940
[Guest]: It interfered in everything from the speaker's powers to election commission, to how parliament

01:09:29.940 --> 01:09:33.620
[Guest]: must be run, to how tax policy must be made.

01:09:33.620 --> 01:09:41.060
[Guest]: Now we are in a giant mess where it is very difficult to roll back this kind of authority

01:09:41.060 --> 01:09:45.060
[Guest]: without actually interfering with the independence of the courts.

01:09:45.060 --> 01:09:48.700
[Guest]: And so now what do we do is kind of the big question going forward.

01:09:48.700 --> 01:09:52.180
[Amit Varma]: So our problem is really now a who will watch the watchman kind of problem.

01:09:52.180 --> 01:09:53.700
[Amit Varma]: I just wanted to complete your thought.

01:09:53.700 --> 01:09:57.540
[Amit Varma]: I think we kind of got waylaid where you were saying that there are three views on judicial

01:09:57.540 --> 01:09:58.880
[Amit Varma]: activism.

01:09:58.880 --> 01:10:04.460
[Amit Varma]: One was checks and balances, that they act as a balance on an overactive executive.

01:10:04.460 --> 01:10:06.940
[Amit Varma]: And the second is the whole division of labor thing.

01:10:06.940 --> 01:10:07.940
[Guest]: Oh yes.

01:10:07.940 --> 01:10:09.660
[Guest]: And the third, I forgot to mention the third.

01:10:09.660 --> 01:10:14.180
[Guest]: The third is that the activism must not be self-serving.

01:10:14.180 --> 01:10:19.720
[Guest]: You know, there was a lot of support for the Supreme Court activism as long as it was advocating

01:10:19.720 --> 01:10:22.140
[Guest]: genuinely for the powers of others.

01:10:22.140 --> 01:10:25.460
[Guest]: You know, the Vishakha case is a classic example.

01:10:25.460 --> 01:10:27.420
[Guest]: Did they legislate from the bench?

01:10:27.420 --> 01:10:28.420
[Guest]: Yes.

01:10:28.420 --> 01:10:31.580
[Guest]: As a constitutional economist, do I think that's a good idea?

01:10:31.580 --> 01:10:32.580
[Guest]: Absolutely not.

01:10:32.580 --> 01:10:33.580
[Guest]: Right.

01:10:33.580 --> 01:10:38.580
[Guest]: But was that public support and intellectual support and legal support for the case?

01:10:38.580 --> 01:10:39.580
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:10:39.580 --> 01:10:42.940
[Guest]: I mean, worldwide, it was a landmark judgment.

01:10:42.940 --> 01:10:47.700
[Guest]: It has been cited in opinions in Europe, in America, in Africa.

01:10:47.700 --> 01:10:54.220
[Guest]: It's really an extraordinary case in the sense that the court stepped up when virtually no

01:10:54.220 --> 01:10:56.100
[Guest]: other public institutions stepped up.

01:10:56.100 --> 01:10:57.820
[Guest]: And frankly, they made rules, right?

01:10:57.820 --> 01:11:01.980
[Guest]: They put in rules and guidelines, which is what the courts do from time to time.

01:11:01.980 --> 01:11:03.340
[Guest]: They fill in gaps in law.

01:11:03.340 --> 01:11:07.380
[Guest]: Now, in this case, of course, they created law from scratch, but it is still somewhat

01:11:07.380 --> 01:11:11.420
[Guest]: within their functional expertise, but it was not self-serving, right?

01:11:11.420 --> 01:11:16.540
[Guest]: If you look at the second and third judge's case, it's a completely self-serving document,

01:11:16.540 --> 01:11:17.540
[Guest]: right?

01:11:17.540 --> 01:11:19.140
[Guest]: It is all about their power.

01:11:19.140 --> 01:11:20.360
[Guest]: Now think about it.

01:11:20.360 --> 01:11:26.340
[Guest]: If you were genuinely interested in independence of judiciary, wouldn't you increase retirement

01:11:26.340 --> 01:11:31.140
[Guest]: age and completely ban Supreme Court justices from taking any government appointment after

01:11:31.140 --> 01:11:33.700
[Guest]: their term is over?

01:11:33.700 --> 01:11:36.860
[Guest]: That is crucial to independence, right?

01:11:36.860 --> 01:11:39.620
[Guest]: But they don't really care about independence.

01:11:39.620 --> 01:11:43.700
[Guest]: They care about the fact that they should be allowed to do whatever they want, but also

01:11:43.700 --> 01:11:45.100
[Guest]: have their cake and eat it too, right?

01:11:45.100 --> 01:11:49.580
[Guest]: So if they want to go the other way and lobby for some government posting, they should be

01:11:49.580 --> 01:11:51.260
[Guest]: allowed to do that too.

01:11:51.260 --> 01:11:55.680
[Guest]: So I think the court has been very self-serving and disingenuous.

01:11:55.680 --> 01:12:01.500
[Guest]: So in some sense, this is not so much about rules and checks and balances, but about the

01:12:01.500 --> 01:12:03.940
[Guest]: functional legitimacy of the court.

01:12:03.940 --> 01:12:09.740
[Guest]: People are more likely to accept an activist court than the activist court is once again

01:12:09.740 --> 01:12:16.820
[Guest]: run by statesmen who know when to do the right thing, and we have not had those people.

01:12:16.820 --> 01:12:20.340
[Guest]: Now the public choice in you and me would say, hey, these horrible rules would never

01:12:20.340 --> 01:12:21.940
[Guest]: produce the right people, right?

01:12:21.940 --> 01:12:24.540
[Guest]: The worst get on top, true.

01:12:24.540 --> 01:12:30.300
[Guest]: But once upon a time, we did have genuine statesmen, activists as they were, right?

01:12:30.300 --> 01:12:36.340
[Guest]: Krishna here was an extremely activist judge, wrote horrible judgments, created a lot of

01:12:36.340 --> 01:12:41.260
[Guest]: problems in labor law and labor jurisprudence that we have until today.

01:12:41.260 --> 01:12:43.700
[Guest]: But none of it was self-serving.

01:12:43.700 --> 01:12:48.580
[Amit Varma]: I think, you know, in the public choice column that I write for Bloomberg Quint, I think

01:12:48.580 --> 01:12:53.420
[Amit Varma]: the first of those examined the question of, in the context of politics, why we had such

01:12:53.420 --> 01:12:58.300
[Amit Varma]: outstanding leaders in the post-immediate, post-independence generation, and we don't

01:12:58.300 --> 01:12:59.300
[Amit Varma]: today.

01:12:59.300 --> 01:13:03.660
[Amit Varma]: And I think the same reason would apply to justices to some extent as well, which is

01:13:03.660 --> 01:13:09.020
[Amit Varma]: that it's a residue of a time where the incentives were different for people to get into politics.

01:13:09.020 --> 01:13:13.260
[Amit Varma]: If you got into politics or public service in those days, there wasn't so much in it

01:13:13.260 --> 01:13:16.820
[Amit Varma]: for you, you were less likely to be driven by the lust for power or money.

01:13:16.820 --> 01:13:21.180
[Amit Varma]: I mean, obviously, none of our freedom fighters had access to any of that in any case.

01:13:21.180 --> 01:13:24.820
[Amit Varma]: And you were more likely to be animated by higher principles.

01:13:24.820 --> 01:13:28.940
[Amit Varma]: And I'd say that it's kind of inevitable that given the shoddy rules that we have, that

01:13:28.940 --> 01:13:34.260
[Amit Varma]: we will end up over a period of time with a bunch of scoundrels, both in politics and

01:13:34.260 --> 01:13:35.500
[Amit Varma]: in the judiciary.

01:13:35.500 --> 01:13:40.700
[Guest]: I completely agree with that, that over a period of time, if you have a bad set of rules

01:13:40.700 --> 01:13:46.260
[Guest]: that actually don't check people and don't constrain people, then it creates a situation

01:13:46.260 --> 01:13:53.060
[Guest]: where you have, you know, that there will be enough, you know, sort of crazy people

01:13:53.060 --> 01:13:57.420
[Guest]: in society or self-serving people in society who will try and manipulate those rules to

01:13:57.420 --> 01:13:58.420
[Guest]: their benefit.

01:13:58.420 --> 01:14:03.380
[Guest]: And if the bad rules and systems continue over a period of long time, then there is

01:14:03.380 --> 01:14:06.180
[Guest]: no question that eventually that group will take over.

01:14:06.180 --> 01:14:08.700
[Guest]: And that's exactly what has happened with the judiciary.

01:14:08.700 --> 01:14:13.760
[Guest]: You know, we talk about dynastic politics and nepotism, there is no institution with

01:14:13.760 --> 01:14:17.940
[Guest]: greater nepotism than the court system in India.

01:14:17.940 --> 01:14:24.260
[Guest]: You know, I mean, we have way more number of father-son, you know, Supreme Court justices

01:14:24.260 --> 01:14:29.500
[Guest]: pairs than we have, you know, father-son or brother pairs of chief ministers or prime

01:14:29.500 --> 01:14:31.260
[Guest]: ministers or something like that.

01:14:31.260 --> 01:14:36.620
[Guest]: Now, there is a, one part of it is all of India is dynastic, right, you know, the son

01:14:36.620 --> 01:14:41.020
[Guest]: of a potter becomes a potter kind of problem, but there is also a question of nepotism and

01:14:41.020 --> 01:14:45.780
[Guest]: connections and, you know, do you know how to navigate the system and hobnob with the

01:14:45.780 --> 01:14:48.580
[Guest]: right people such that they nominate you to the bench.

01:14:48.580 --> 01:14:53.660
[Guest]: And when the judicial system is completely insular in its appointment systems, this is

01:14:53.660 --> 01:14:55.660
[Guest]: just far more likely to happen.

01:14:55.660 --> 01:15:01.340
[Guest]: Also, this is the kind of situation where you get a lot of possibilities of sexual harassment

01:15:01.340 --> 01:15:02.340
[Guest]: and so on.

01:15:02.340 --> 01:15:03.340
[Guest]: Right.

01:15:03.340 --> 01:15:05.020
[Guest]: Now, think about it.

01:15:05.020 --> 01:15:08.060
[Guest]: If the Chief Justice of India, now that's not what happened in the current case.

01:15:08.060 --> 01:15:14.380
[Guest]: The current case, the complainant is not a judge, okay, but is a staff member.

01:15:14.380 --> 01:15:20.620
[Guest]: But you can very easily imagine, right, if enough women make it to the bench, the day

01:15:20.620 --> 01:15:25.980
[Guest]: is not far that if all the appointments are controlled by these five men right on top,

01:15:25.980 --> 01:15:27.380
[Guest]: that they can abuse their power.

01:15:27.380 --> 01:15:31.740
[Guest]: Now, we haven't had that problem yet because there are so few women in the system.

01:15:31.740 --> 01:15:36.580
[Guest]: You know, I don't know if that's a benefit or a problem, but so far we haven't had that.

01:15:36.580 --> 01:15:40.860
[Guest]: But very soon you're going to see those kinds of problems also.

01:15:40.860 --> 01:15:46.220
[Guest]: And I think the biggest problem is when the court system does things like this, it is

01:15:46.220 --> 01:15:49.540
[Guest]: legitimacy in the eyes of the public.

01:15:49.540 --> 01:15:53.700
[Guest]: Justice must be done, but it must also seem to be done, right?

01:15:53.700 --> 01:15:57.020
[Guest]: In some sense, this is all a bit of a magic trick, right?

01:15:57.020 --> 01:16:00.620
[Guest]: We all believe that magic is happening and then it's happening.

01:16:00.620 --> 01:16:05.900
[Guest]: Now, if we start questioning that this is really not what it seems to be, the whole

01:16:05.900 --> 01:16:11.220
[Guest]: institution will come down like a pack of cards because the court doesn't really have

01:16:11.220 --> 01:16:14.660
[Guest]: any power of its own aside from public legitimacy.

01:16:14.660 --> 01:16:18.460
[Guest]: It doesn't control the purse strings and it doesn't control the sword, right?

01:16:18.460 --> 01:16:24.700
[Guest]: So the court system only survives if the people who are vested in the court system think that

01:16:24.700 --> 01:16:26.820
[Guest]: it has a right to exist.

01:16:26.820 --> 01:16:31.100
[Guest]: So if there are more situations like this, which is basically a problem propagated by

01:16:31.100 --> 01:16:38.300
[Guest]: the appointment system, but if there are more situations like Chief Justice Mishra who sat

01:16:38.300 --> 01:16:44.820
[Guest]: in his own cause and same as this current Chief Justice Gogoi who sat in a matter in

01:16:44.820 --> 01:16:48.780
[Guest]: his own cause, very soon that legitimacy will be lost.

01:16:48.780 --> 01:16:52.520
[Guest]: So that's a problem and it can't be fixed overnight.

01:16:52.520 --> 01:16:56.780
[Guest]: You can get rid of a bad judge overnight, but this public legitimacy, it just can't

01:16:56.780 --> 01:16:57.780
[Amit Varma]: be fixed overnight.

01:16:57.780 --> 01:17:02.060
[Amit Varma]: This whole situation of, you know, a judge sitting in a case where he is the accused

01:17:02.060 --> 01:17:06.620
[Amit Varma]: feels to me like, you know, the batting side in a cricket match also being the umpire.

01:17:06.620 --> 01:17:11.420
[Amit Varma]: So the captain of the batting side will decide whether somebody is out LBW or not.

01:17:11.420 --> 01:17:12.420
[Amit Varma]: It's ludicrous.

01:17:12.420 --> 01:17:13.420
[Amit Varma]: And I had an episode.

01:17:13.420 --> 01:17:17.580
[Guest]: Can I, can I give you, interrupt and give you an example of that?

01:17:17.580 --> 01:17:18.580
[Guest]: Sure.

01:17:18.580 --> 01:17:24.020
[Guest]: When we were kids playing cricket, the person who owned the bat decided whether that person

01:17:24.020 --> 01:17:25.020
[Guest]: was out or not.

01:17:25.020 --> 01:17:27.500
[Guest]: I don't know if this was your experience.

01:17:27.500 --> 01:17:32.980
[Guest]: But the kid who owned the bat never got out because we all had to wait our turn to bat

01:17:32.980 --> 01:17:34.580
[Guest]: because we didn't have one.

01:17:34.580 --> 01:17:36.100
[Guest]: So it's a little bit like that also.

01:17:36.100 --> 01:17:38.220
[Guest]: You see a lot of that happening in India.

01:17:38.220 --> 01:17:39.220
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:17:39.220 --> 01:17:42.940
[Amit Varma]: And I had an episode a year back on judicial reforms with my friend Alok Prasanna Kumar.

01:17:42.940 --> 01:17:46.220
[Amit Varma]: And you know, he made a very similar point to what you're making now, where he spoke

01:17:46.220 --> 01:17:50.820
[Amit Varma]: about how our Supreme Court has a diversity problem.

01:17:50.820 --> 01:17:55.460
[Amit Varma]: And in my mind, the ramification of this is not just in terms of representation and so

01:17:55.460 --> 01:18:00.420
[Amit Varma]: on in a democracy, but also it impacts decision making, like one of the best books I've read

01:18:00.420 --> 01:18:05.100
[Amit Varma]: in the last few years is a book by Philip Tetlock called Super Forecasting, which refers

01:18:05.100 --> 01:18:13.340
[Amit Varma]: to a study which showed that the most important parameter for good decision making is diversity.

01:18:13.340 --> 01:18:17.180
[Amit Varma]: It's not intelligence, it's not knowledge, it's not or any of those things, but diversity.

01:18:17.180 --> 01:18:22.140
[Amit Varma]: And the more diverse that a group is, the more likely you are to make good decisions.

01:18:22.140 --> 01:18:25.580
[Amit Varma]: For example, you spoke about the judicial activism of the Delhi High Court earlier,

01:18:25.580 --> 01:18:29.140
[Amit Varma]: where they spoke about, you know, all the buses have to go CNG.

01:18:29.140 --> 01:18:32.460
[Amit Varma]: And you imagine that if the court was diverse enough that there are people who've actually

01:18:32.460 --> 01:18:39.860
[Amit Varma]: grown up riding around in buses and auto rickshaws, maybe they might have had greater foresight

01:18:39.860 --> 01:18:42.980
[Amit Varma]: in that situation and not done what they did.

01:18:42.980 --> 01:18:48.580
[Amit Varma]: But that aside, so you know, what I see here is a worst of both possible worlds.

01:18:48.580 --> 01:18:53.580
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand, the judiciary is not quite independent from the executive because of

01:18:53.580 --> 01:19:00.420
[Amit Varma]: bad incentives in play, such as post retirement options, where the government can always hold

01:19:00.420 --> 01:19:06.060
[Amit Varma]: out carrots in front of judges and say that, okay, after you retire, this is what you get

01:19:06.060 --> 01:19:08.820
[Amit Varma]: and you get that car with the red button on top.

01:19:08.820 --> 01:19:15.060
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, it is also too powerful in and of itself because it controls the appointment

01:19:15.060 --> 01:19:19.940
[Amit Varma]: process through the collegium, the second judge's case of 1993, as you pointed out,

01:19:19.940 --> 01:19:25.580
[Amit Varma]: a case of judicial activism, which was actually self-serving.

01:19:25.580 --> 01:19:27.780
[Amit Varma]: So this is like a double problem now.

01:19:27.780 --> 01:19:28.780
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:19:28.780 --> 01:19:29.780
[Guest]: How do we solve this?

01:19:29.780 --> 01:19:31.020
[Guest]: It's very difficult to solve it.

01:19:31.020 --> 01:19:37.780
[Guest]: So you know, in, you know, all credit to the Modi government, they tried, okay, they passed

01:19:37.780 --> 01:19:41.620
[Guest]: a constitutional amendment, which was called the NJAC, you know, the National Judicial

01:19:41.620 --> 01:19:42.620
[Guest]: Collegium.

01:19:42.620 --> 01:19:49.420
[Guest]: They amended article 124 to 17, and basically they changed the appointment procedure in

01:19:49.420 --> 01:19:51.300
[Guest]: the formal text of the constitution.

01:19:51.300 --> 01:19:54.140
[Guest]: So it was a full constitutional amendment, right?

01:19:54.140 --> 01:19:58.220
[Guest]: And this constitutional amendment basically said that the collegium will not just have

01:19:58.220 --> 01:20:00.140
[Guest]: members of the judiciary.

01:20:00.140 --> 01:20:05.660
[Guest]: So the collegium will be the chief justice of India and two justices, but it will also

01:20:05.660 --> 01:20:07.460
[Guest]: represent the law minister.

01:20:07.460 --> 01:20:12.460
[Guest]: So one position out of six will go to the executive, three positions out of six will

01:20:12.460 --> 01:20:13.460
[Guest]: be the judiciary.

01:20:13.460 --> 01:20:16.380
[Guest]: That is the CJI and the next two senior most justices.

01:20:16.380 --> 01:20:22.020
[Guest]: And it had a provision that there will be two eminent persons who will be on this collegium,

01:20:22.020 --> 01:20:23.020
[Guest]: right?

01:20:23.020 --> 01:20:29.500
[Guest]: And I think the idea behind this was, look, there is a problem with the executive having

01:20:29.500 --> 01:20:35.380
[Guest]: a 50% stake because, you know, the government of India, both the union and the state governments

01:20:35.380 --> 01:20:39.140
[Guest]: is the largest litigant before the court, right?

01:20:39.140 --> 01:20:43.060
[Guest]: So in that sense, it's a problem to have too much representation.

01:20:43.060 --> 01:20:46.100
[Guest]: So they kept it down to one person, right?

01:20:46.100 --> 01:20:51.180
[Guest]: And they had this for, you know, two eminent people from society sort of provision.

01:20:51.180 --> 01:20:54.580
[Guest]: And there was also provision that there should be enough women and minorities, right?

01:20:54.580 --> 01:21:00.500
[Guest]: Within the group that chooses these eminent persons and three from the judiciary.

01:21:00.500 --> 01:21:05.460
[Guest]: Now, it is not the best system according to me, but I think it would have still been an

01:21:05.460 --> 01:21:09.240
[Guest]: improvement over the current system, right?

01:21:09.240 --> 01:21:12.940
[Guest]: Because there was a genuine recognition that the executive needs to participate, but not

01:21:12.940 --> 01:21:14.980
[Guest]: participate too much.

01:21:14.980 --> 01:21:20.260
[Guest]: And the Supreme Court struck this constitutional amendment down saying it violates the basic

01:21:20.260 --> 01:21:23.420
[Guest]: structure and went back to the system of the collegium.

01:21:23.420 --> 01:21:24.420
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

01:21:24.420 --> 01:21:29.740
[Amit Varma]: So you can't actually, so they get to rule on anything which affects them using the excuse

01:21:29.740 --> 01:21:30.740
[Guest]: of the basic structure.

01:21:30.740 --> 01:21:32.940
[Guest]: Yeah, using the basic structure.

01:21:32.940 --> 01:21:33.940
[Guest]: So this is a problem.

01:21:33.940 --> 01:21:36.900
[Guest]: And then what happened was, I mean, the executive is also clever.

01:21:36.900 --> 01:21:41.420
[Guest]: So the cabinet didn't appoint judges for a long time.

01:21:41.420 --> 01:21:46.300
[Guest]: You know, I think this last week we are finally operating at a full strength of the bench,

01:21:46.300 --> 01:21:47.300
[Guest]: right?

01:21:47.300 --> 01:21:51.040
[Guest]: So the chief justice would send names and the cabinet just won't appoint them.

01:21:51.040 --> 01:21:52.040
[Guest]: So what can you do?

01:21:52.040 --> 01:21:53.040
[Guest]: Right?

01:21:53.040 --> 01:21:56.360
[Guest]: So they were in deadlock, which basically meant justice suffered because the bench is

01:21:56.360 --> 01:21:58.940
[Guest]: not operating at its full strength, right?

01:21:58.940 --> 01:22:03.020
[Guest]: So the cabinet was very clever in that they didn't do anything overt.

01:22:03.020 --> 01:22:05.500
[Guest]: But they also knew when to dig their heels.

01:22:05.500 --> 01:22:09.620
[Guest]: So now it is a more collaborative process, but there are some other very big problems

01:22:09.620 --> 01:22:10.860
[Guest]: with this, right?

01:22:10.860 --> 01:22:15.040
[Guest]: Now let's say they wanted to be completely insular.

01:22:15.040 --> 01:22:18.660
[Guest]: That is, it was the chief justice of India plus four justices.

01:22:18.660 --> 01:22:22.940
[Guest]: It would be so much better still if they made the procedure transparent.

01:22:22.940 --> 01:22:27.940
[Guest]: That is, if the collegium sat and they actually took down minutes to the meeting.

01:22:27.940 --> 01:22:32.900
[Guest]: In every meeting they told you how many of the members of these five, you know, members

01:22:32.900 --> 01:22:36.980
[Guest]: of the collegium support every appointment or oppose every appointment.

01:22:36.980 --> 01:22:39.100
[Guest]: None of this exists.

01:22:39.100 --> 01:22:43.340
[Guest]: You know, since the second judge's case, and you know, it's confirmation in the third judge's

01:22:43.340 --> 01:22:47.420
[Guest]: case, we don't have any minutes to collegium meetings.

01:22:47.420 --> 01:22:48.420
[Guest]: They don't exist.

01:22:48.420 --> 01:22:49.420
[Guest]: Right?

01:22:49.420 --> 01:22:54.820
[Guest]: And if they did exist, which institution has the authority to subpoena them?

01:22:54.820 --> 01:22:55.820
[Guest]: No one.

01:22:55.820 --> 01:22:58.420
[Guest]: So how can we demand to see these minutes?

01:22:58.420 --> 01:23:04.260
[Guest]: So the procedures that came about in the third judge's case, which the Supreme Court had

01:23:04.260 --> 01:23:08.300
[Guest]: enforced, they are not being followed by the Supreme Court.

01:23:08.300 --> 01:23:11.940
[Guest]: So the Supreme Court is sort of running its own like gundaraj kind of thing, right?

01:23:11.940 --> 01:23:13.940
[Guest]: It does whatever it wants.

01:23:13.940 --> 01:23:19.740
[Guest]: Justice Chellameshwar actually came forward and said that I am in the collegium, but it

01:23:19.740 --> 01:23:24.340
[Guest]: is not recording meetings and it's not recording dissent, right?

01:23:24.340 --> 01:23:27.780
[Guest]: If you remember last year, there was that famous press conference by the four senior

01:23:27.780 --> 01:23:32.820
[Guest]: most judges against Chief Justice Deepak Mishra about the master of the roster and all of

01:23:32.820 --> 01:23:33.820
[Guest]: those things.

01:23:33.820 --> 01:23:36.260
[Guest]: And one of those issues was also the collegium.

01:23:36.260 --> 01:23:44.300
[Guest]: So there is a really big problem in that the courts think that any requirement of disclosure

01:23:44.300 --> 01:23:48.060
[Guest]: or scrutiny is a threat to their independence, which is simply not true.

01:23:48.060 --> 01:23:53.260
[Guest]: I mean, this is just really, it's sort of like, you know, in the Soviet, the Duma, there

01:23:53.260 --> 01:23:59.780
[Guest]: was one of the protections was that there can't be any criminal charges against members

01:23:59.780 --> 01:24:00.780
[Guest]: of the Duma.

01:24:00.780 --> 01:24:02.500
[Guest]: So guess what happened?

01:24:02.500 --> 01:24:04.580
[Guest]: All the criminals ended up in the Duma, right?

01:24:04.580 --> 01:24:09.780
[Guest]: So it's one of those sort of things where if you create a system where you are completely

01:24:09.780 --> 01:24:14.260
[Guest]: above scrutiny, then only those people who really wish to be above scrutiny are going

01:24:14.260 --> 01:24:15.940
[Guest]: to lobby for these spots.

01:24:15.940 --> 01:24:20.540
[Guest]: All good decent people are going to sort of stay away from the system because if you're

01:24:20.540 --> 01:24:25.420
[Guest]: not a politically motivated judge, you won't survive in this current judicial jungle of

01:24:25.420 --> 01:24:26.860
[Guest]: the collegium.

01:24:26.860 --> 01:24:28.380
[Guest]: So this is sort of the problem.

01:24:28.380 --> 01:24:33.220
[Guest]: There are some other problems also, like the retirement age is frankly too low.

01:24:33.220 --> 01:24:35.380
[Guest]: And particularly with reference to the high court.

01:24:35.380 --> 01:24:37.900
[Guest]: So you know, the high court retirement age is 62.

01:24:37.900 --> 01:24:42.380
[Guest]: So the way it works is mostly Supreme Court justices are promoted up from the high court

01:24:42.380 --> 01:24:46.300
[Guest]: and mostly it is when the high court judges retire.

01:24:46.300 --> 01:24:51.860
[Guest]: So the average term of a Supreme Court justice is just around two years.

01:24:51.860 --> 01:24:55.580
[Guest]: And the average term of a chief justice is about six to eight months.

01:24:55.580 --> 01:25:00.380
[Guest]: We've had chief justices who've served three weeks because of the seniority rule.

01:25:00.380 --> 01:25:05.820
[Guest]: So there is a lot of churn at the top, you know, so that is one very, very big problem.

01:25:05.820 --> 01:25:10.780
[Guest]: That's a diversity problem also, because if most of your judges are coming up from the

01:25:10.780 --> 01:25:17.180
[Guest]: high court, then you are getting a very sort of like monochromatic picture of what the

01:25:17.180 --> 01:25:19.580
[Guest]: judiciary needs to look like.

01:25:19.580 --> 01:25:22.860
[Guest]: Everyone looks the same and has the same kind of experience.

01:25:22.860 --> 01:25:29.820
[Guest]: Now, if you read books about the judiciary originally by George Gadboy, you know, who's

01:25:29.820 --> 01:25:34.340
[Guest]: done profiles of all the judges, you will notice that even initially both the high court

01:25:34.340 --> 01:25:41.020
[Guest]: and the Supreme Court were mostly men, upper caste Brahmin men who had some legal training

01:25:41.020 --> 01:25:45.500
[Guest]: and had family, which was like a family of lawyers, right?

01:25:45.500 --> 01:25:52.300
[Guest]: So there wasn't too much diversity when we began either, but it seems to have gotten

01:25:52.300 --> 01:25:53.300
[Guest]: worse.

01:25:53.300 --> 01:25:56.660
[Guest]: There was a little more diversity of thought because they came from different high courts

01:25:56.660 --> 01:26:04.380
[Guest]: and different backgrounds personally, but now it's all very elite, upper caste, privileged

01:26:04.380 --> 01:26:08.700
[Guest]: people whose family have excellent legal and political connections who are sort of moving

01:26:08.700 --> 01:26:11.260
[Guest]: up the bench in the court system.

01:26:11.260 --> 01:26:16.900
[Guest]: And there is a really big problem of minority representation in terms of other religions,

01:26:16.900 --> 01:26:19.500
[Guest]: women, Dalit community.

01:26:19.500 --> 01:26:22.020
[Guest]: It's a really big problem right now, right?

01:26:22.020 --> 01:26:27.860
[Guest]: So it's both diversity of individuals in terms of identity and also diversity of ideas.

01:26:27.860 --> 01:26:31.980
[Guest]: Like you said, you know, if you've never ridden in a bus, you don't know the problems of shutting

01:26:31.980 --> 01:26:33.560
[Guest]: down a bus service.

01:26:33.560 --> 01:26:35.740
[Guest]: So it's a little bit of both.

01:26:35.740 --> 01:26:39.300
[Guest]: And the Supreme Court is now completely captured by this mess.

01:26:39.300 --> 01:26:43.180
[Guest]: And it's not easy in terms of what is the way out of this.

01:26:43.180 --> 01:26:49.340
[Guest]: I mean, the new Modi government could have some renewed pressure.

01:26:49.340 --> 01:26:56.460
[Guest]: You know, I mean, this new term has got such a loud and large mandate in favor of Narendra

01:26:56.460 --> 01:27:03.220
[Guest]: Modi and given the complete mess that has been made by the Supreme Court in the last

01:27:03.220 --> 01:27:09.060
[Guest]: year and a half, it is possible that if another constitutional amendment is pushed forth with

01:27:09.060 --> 01:27:14.820
[Guest]: a sensible set of appointment rules and procedures, it is possible that the public will support

01:27:14.820 --> 01:27:19.220
[Guest]: the government and not the Supreme Court for the first time in a very long time.

01:27:19.220 --> 01:27:20.900
[Guest]: So there are some possibilities.

01:27:20.900 --> 01:27:21.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:27:21.900 --> 01:27:26.860
[Amit Varma]: So I should point out to my listeners that we're actually recording this on May 23rd,

01:27:26.860 --> 01:27:29.540
[Amit Varma]: which is the date of the election results.

01:27:29.540 --> 01:27:30.780
[Amit Varma]: They've just been announced today morning.

01:27:30.780 --> 01:27:34.620
[Amit Varma]: We're recording this in the evening, which is why we are not talking about the executive

01:27:34.620 --> 01:27:38.380
[Amit Varma]: or the legislature, but about the Supreme Court, silly.

01:27:38.380 --> 01:27:44.060
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that in all of this, there is a sort of this fundamental trade off that

01:27:44.060 --> 01:27:48.780
[Amit Varma]: has to be made between on the one hand, the independence of the judiciary, which is important,

01:27:48.780 --> 01:27:55.220
[Amit Varma]: but on the other hand, between the accountability of the judiciary, which also matters a great

01:27:55.220 --> 01:27:56.220
[Amit Varma]: deal.

01:27:56.220 --> 01:27:57.220
[Guest]: Now, I want to ask you.

01:27:57.220 --> 01:28:02.940
[Guest]: And thirdly, the competence, frankly, I mean, I mean, if you read the more recent judgments

01:28:02.940 --> 01:28:06.180
[Guest]: and opinions, they are just a horror.

01:28:06.180 --> 01:28:10.620
[Guest]: I mean, and when I say a horror, I'm not being a snob like, oh, you know, it's grammatically

01:28:10.620 --> 01:28:11.940
[Guest]: incorrect or not formatted.

01:28:11.940 --> 01:28:19.180
[Guest]: I really mean, in terms of points of fact and points of law, these judges seem to have

01:28:19.180 --> 01:28:24.540
[Guest]: just come out of nowhere, and they seem to just write whatever flies into their mind.

01:28:24.540 --> 01:28:28.020
[Guest]: And there is no sensible reasoning.

01:28:28.020 --> 01:28:31.320
[Guest]: Reason has left the Supreme Court building completely.

01:28:31.320 --> 01:28:34.260
[Guest]: So that is, I think, the greatest loss in all of this.

01:28:34.260 --> 01:28:40.140
[Guest]: We are having a huge body of law, but that law has no reason in it.

01:28:40.140 --> 01:28:46.460
[Guest]: So it is not very useful in terms of being binding as, you know, precedent in the future,

01:28:46.460 --> 01:28:52.140
[Guest]: because we don't have any sensible, like, doctrinal analysis on why is it that the courts

01:28:52.140 --> 01:28:56.940
[Guest]: have come to this opinion or, you know, landed on one side or the other side in this particular

01:28:56.940 --> 01:28:57.940
[Guest]: case.

01:28:57.940 --> 01:29:03.860
[Guest]: So it's, what is being lost is more than just, oh, I don't like this Supreme Court judge

01:29:03.860 --> 01:29:06.860
[Guest]: and there's a sexual harassment against that Supreme Court justice.

01:29:06.860 --> 01:29:08.900
[Guest]: That's really not the only thing at stake.

01:29:08.900 --> 01:29:15.820
[Guest]: There is a huge missed opportunity on what is a sensible body of law and rules.

01:29:15.820 --> 01:29:19.340
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of quick questions before we wind it up.

01:29:19.340 --> 01:29:24.020
[Amit Varma]: Number one, from within the judiciary, there have been voices of dissent and change, including

01:29:24.020 --> 01:29:25.980
[Amit Varma]: from the Supreme Court itself.

01:29:25.980 --> 01:29:30.140
[Amit Varma]: What is driving those voices and how likely are they to succeed?

01:29:30.140 --> 01:29:36.100
[Amit Varma]: And number two, you spoke about the NJAC constitutional amendment that the last Modi government tried

01:29:36.100 --> 01:29:39.300
[Amit Varma]: and you pointed out about how it would be a good measure.

01:29:39.300 --> 01:29:43.500
[Amit Varma]: What was driving the attempt by the government to sort of get that amendment through?

01:29:43.500 --> 01:29:45.220
[Amit Varma]: What are their incentives?

01:29:45.220 --> 01:29:53.420
[Guest]: So, you know, I would say, you know, despite my other reservations with a lot of Modi government's

01:29:53.420 --> 01:29:59.620
[Guest]: policies on the NJAC matter, they were fairly restrained.

01:29:59.620 --> 01:30:02.180
[Guest]: You know, I must give credit where credit is due.

01:30:02.180 --> 01:30:06.740
[Guest]: And this is obviously in comparison to the horrors of Indira Gandhi and the emergency,

01:30:06.740 --> 01:30:07.740
[Guest]: right?

01:30:07.740 --> 01:30:12.700
[Guest]: So they could have done a lot worse given the kind of popularity and mandate they had,

01:30:12.700 --> 01:30:14.060
[Guest]: but they were fairly restrained.

01:30:14.060 --> 01:30:15.700
[Guest]: They tried to do it properly.

01:30:15.700 --> 01:30:21.660
[Guest]: They tried to do it through a proper constitutional amendment procedure and the amendment had

01:30:21.660 --> 01:30:25.820
[Guest]: a lot of problems, but it wasn't the worst thing that had been suggested and it was probably

01:30:25.820 --> 01:30:27.860
[Guest]: an improvement over the past.

01:30:27.860 --> 01:30:31.540
[Guest]: So that is the first thing I want to say about that.

01:30:31.540 --> 01:30:38.220
[Guest]: The second is, I think the revolution has to come from within if it has to have legitimacy.

01:30:38.220 --> 01:30:42.580
[Guest]: So you know, I wrote a column a few months ago saying the Supreme Court needs to have

01:30:42.580 --> 01:30:44.460
[Guest]: a Ulysses fact.

01:30:44.460 --> 01:30:47.780
[Guest]: So you know the story of Ulysses and the sirens?

01:30:47.780 --> 01:30:54.940
[Amit Varma]: You remind my listeners, which is one way of saying, I know, but remind my listeners.

01:30:54.940 --> 01:31:04.500
[Guest]: So Ulysses or, you know, the Odyssey, so him, when he returns from the wars and travels

01:31:04.500 --> 01:31:11.380
[Guest]: and he's on the ship with all his men, he realizes that he is going to get distracted

01:31:11.380 --> 01:31:15.860
[Guest]: by the sound or the music of the sirens, right?

01:31:15.860 --> 01:31:18.300
[Guest]: And what Ulysses does is quite interesting.

01:31:18.300 --> 01:31:23.900
[Guest]: He pours wax into the ears of all his men so that they are not distracted by the sound

01:31:23.900 --> 01:31:25.380
[Guest]: of the sirens.

01:31:25.380 --> 01:31:33.060
[Guest]: And then he ties himself to the mast of the ship and tells his men not to untie him, right?

01:31:33.060 --> 01:31:37.260
[Guest]: So this is basically like the legend or the mythical version.

01:31:37.260 --> 01:31:43.180
[Guest]: The idea is that you must tie your own hands because you know that your future self, when

01:31:43.180 --> 01:31:47.080
[Guest]: faced with the terrible incentives, will not be able to do the right thing.

01:31:47.080 --> 01:31:52.100
[Guest]: But your current self already knows that, so you must take precautions for it, right?

01:31:52.100 --> 01:31:57.940
[Guest]: So if Ulysses has no one else to monitor and govern him the way he could monitor his men

01:31:57.940 --> 01:32:02.940
[Guest]: and pour wax in his ears, then it is upon Ulysses to tie himself to the mast.

01:32:02.940 --> 01:32:04.300
[Guest]: That's sort of the idea.

01:32:04.300 --> 01:32:10.100
[Guest]: So this legend or folklore was, you know, invoked by John Elster when he spoke about

01:32:10.100 --> 01:32:11.700
[Guest]: constitutional constraints.

01:32:11.700 --> 01:32:13.360
[Guest]: So that's where this comes from.

01:32:13.360 --> 01:32:18.300
[Guest]: So I had written a column that said that the Indian Supreme Court needs its own Ulysses

01:32:18.300 --> 01:32:25.940
[Guest]: Pact, which is they need to come up with a system of internal rules and protocols on

01:32:25.940 --> 01:32:29.940
[Guest]: appointment, on retirement age, and they need to stick by it, right?

01:32:29.940 --> 01:32:32.740
[Guest]: Now these are experts in lawmaking, right?

01:32:32.740 --> 01:32:36.660
[Guest]: So they need to create a culture where they come up with a very clear set of rules on

01:32:36.660 --> 01:32:40.500
[Guest]: appointment and they have disclosure requirements, right?

01:32:40.500 --> 01:32:42.100
[Guest]: So that's one way.

01:32:42.100 --> 01:32:46.860
[Guest]: Another is they need to have protocols for recusal, which is if you are adjudicating

01:32:46.860 --> 01:32:51.460
[Guest]: your own case or it's come before your bench, when must you recuse yourself and when can

01:32:51.460 --> 01:32:53.500
[Guest]: you continue, right?

01:32:53.500 --> 01:32:57.100
[Guest]: That's another kind of situation that needs protocols.

01:32:57.100 --> 01:33:04.000
[Guest]: Then a third situation that needs protocols is, should there be some kind of like moratorium

01:33:04.000 --> 01:33:09.820
[Guest]: or a gap before you're allowed to take other paid work or, you know, work for the government

01:33:09.820 --> 01:33:10.820
[Guest]: of India?

01:33:10.820 --> 01:33:15.340
[Guest]: You know, you also don't want them working for Adani immediately after they sat on a

01:33:15.340 --> 01:33:20.240
[Guest]: bench which has a judgment affecting the Adani companies or something like that.

01:33:20.240 --> 01:33:23.220
[Guest]: So we need to have rules and protocols for all this.

01:33:23.220 --> 01:33:25.580
[Guest]: And there are two parts to the rules and protocols.

01:33:25.580 --> 01:33:27.580
[Guest]: One is they need to be put down.

01:33:27.580 --> 01:33:34.100
[Guest]: And the second is we do need some leadership within the judiciary to actually enforce this

01:33:34.100 --> 01:33:38.800
[Guest]: over a period of a few years such that they become conventions, right?

01:33:38.800 --> 01:33:40.220
[Guest]: Because it's very difficult.

01:33:40.220 --> 01:33:45.580
[Guest]: I mean, we've tried the bazooka, which is the constitutional amendment, and it has failed.

01:33:45.580 --> 01:33:47.660
[Guest]: And the public was with the judiciary at that time.

01:33:47.660 --> 01:33:54.260
[Guest]: So the judiciary needs to save itself because if they won't let any sunlight from outside,

01:33:54.260 --> 01:33:55.720
[Guest]: they need to come up with a set of rules.

01:33:55.720 --> 01:33:58.940
[Guest]: So that is, I think the number one thing that is required.

01:33:58.940 --> 01:34:03.840
[Guest]: The second possibility is we burn the whole thing down and build it up from scratch, which

01:34:03.840 --> 01:34:07.540
[Guest]: could be done with a strong leader like Narendra Modi, frankly.

01:34:07.540 --> 01:34:13.580
[Guest]: You know, he has such huge public support and mandate that if he said that the Supreme

01:34:13.580 --> 01:34:18.380
[Guest]: Court is extremely corrupt, which it is, and there's too much nepotism and dynastic whatever

01:34:18.380 --> 01:34:22.820
[Guest]: in the Supreme Court, and we need to create a new system by which judges are appointed

01:34:22.820 --> 01:34:28.180
[Guest]: and promoted, it is wholly possible that he might get away with it, right?

01:34:28.180 --> 01:34:32.500
[Guest]: So once again, Narendra Modi will also need a Ulysses pact, like he should not go too

01:34:32.500 --> 01:34:34.980
[Guest]: crazy with the power and the mandate that he has.

01:34:34.980 --> 01:34:39.820
[Amit Varma]: I'm already, I'm already shivering in terror, thinking of Mr. Modi changing the constitution

01:34:39.820 --> 01:34:42.820
[Amit Varma]: and putting a new Supreme Court in place and all of that.

01:34:42.820 --> 01:34:47.420
[Guest]: And yeah, well, it won't be a new Supreme Court in place, but it would be a new set

01:34:47.420 --> 01:34:52.540
[Guest]: of procedures to appoint, which frankly needs to come at some point.

01:34:52.540 --> 01:34:58.540
[Guest]: You know, I mean, it's a little hard and, you know, in all fairness, he's one fair and

01:34:58.540 --> 01:35:05.500
[Guest]: square with a huge vote share, with a huge majority, a larger majority than before, despite

01:35:05.500 --> 01:35:08.220
[Guest]: all his policy failures and successes.

01:35:08.220 --> 01:35:13.740
[Guest]: So if you truly believe in the constitution and democratic decision making, it is very

01:35:13.740 --> 01:35:19.300
[Guest]: complicated to say that I don't like this guy and therefore he shouldn't get involved

01:35:19.300 --> 01:35:21.540
[Guest]: in a constitutional amendment or something like that.

01:35:21.540 --> 01:35:27.060
[Guest]: The only person who has the power to dictate a constitutional amendment is the prime minister

01:35:27.060 --> 01:35:31.620
[Guest]: with the support of parliament, obviously, you know, but it needs to come from the majority

01:35:31.620 --> 01:35:32.620
[Amit Varma]: in parliament.

01:35:32.620 --> 01:35:33.620
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree with that.

01:35:33.620 --> 01:35:37.220
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, all our prime ministers, Nehru onwards, as you've pointed out repeatedly

01:35:37.220 --> 01:35:42.060
[Amit Varma]: have changed the constitution many, many times, and this man has a majority bigger than most

01:35:42.060 --> 01:35:43.060
[Amit Varma]: others.

01:35:43.060 --> 01:35:47.860
[Amit Varma]: But then I would simply worry about the incentives in play if the executive is to try and redesign

01:35:47.860 --> 01:35:53.220
[Amit Varma]: the judicial system, because obviously they would try to redesign it in such a way that

01:35:53.220 --> 01:35:55.380
[Amit Varma]: the institution loses its independence.

01:35:55.380 --> 01:35:59.620
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they might be, you know, Mr. Modi might be an enlightened statesman and might

01:35:59.620 --> 01:36:00.620
[Amit Varma]: not do that.

01:36:00.620 --> 01:36:03.980
[Amit Varma]: But I'm just looking at the incentives and saying, those are the incentives.

01:36:03.980 --> 01:36:08.380
[Guest]: Yeah, but on the other hand, the incentives are pretty bad for the judiciary also to reform

01:36:08.380 --> 01:36:09.380
[Guest]: itself.

01:36:09.380 --> 01:36:12.380
[Guest]: You know, so we're kind of stuck between a rock and a hard place sort of, you know, it's

01:36:12.380 --> 01:36:13.380
[Guest]: really difficult.

01:36:13.380 --> 01:36:20.580
[Guest]: And, you know, these are the sorts of areas where a great leader can really break through,

01:36:20.580 --> 01:36:24.060
[Guest]: you know, there's an incentive problem on both sides, there's an incentive problem on

01:36:24.060 --> 01:36:29.740
[Guest]: all sides, and it does take a great leader to rise above the incentive problem.

01:36:29.740 --> 01:36:34.540
[Guest]: So, you know, it's possible that it could come from like the next chief justice of India

01:36:34.540 --> 01:36:38.540
[Guest]: or the one after, but it's also possible that it comes from Narendra Modi who wants to make

01:36:38.540 --> 01:36:41.220
[Amit Varma]: a place for himself in history, you know.

01:36:41.220 --> 01:36:42.220
[Amit Varma]: That's fair enough.

01:36:42.220 --> 01:36:43.820
[Amit Varma]: And the chief justices change fairly fast, right?

01:36:43.820 --> 01:36:47.820
[Unknown]: So it's as they change very quickly, there is a chance that there'll be some guy who'll

01:36:47.820 --> 01:36:52.300
[Amit Varma]: say, hey, let me, let me seal my legacy by doing this thing, which I know is kind of

01:36:52.300 --> 01:36:53.300
[Guest]: required.

01:36:53.300 --> 01:36:56.660
[Guest]: But the trouble, you know, we kind of need someone who's around for three, four years.

01:36:56.660 --> 01:37:01.060
[Guest]: I'll tell you why we need someone to put the rules in place and enforce them and create

01:37:01.060 --> 01:37:04.820
[Guest]: a culture over 50-60 judges journey.

01:37:04.820 --> 01:37:06.500
[Guest]: You know, that's when it really takes.

01:37:06.500 --> 01:37:12.340
[Guest]: So I think Justice Chandrachud is the next one in line, not immediately, but is the next

01:37:12.340 --> 01:37:15.060
[Guest]: one who will have a fairly long term.

01:37:15.060 --> 01:37:18.100
[Guest]: So my hope is that maybe, you know, his term is long enough.

01:37:18.100 --> 01:37:21.680
[Guest]: You know, this is your classic residual clemency problem, right?

01:37:21.680 --> 01:37:26.300
[Guest]: So initially when we used to talk about courts, we used to say the Kanya court, the Shastri

01:37:26.300 --> 01:37:28.900
[Guest]: court, right, the Bhagwati court.

01:37:28.900 --> 01:37:33.140
[Guest]: So the chief justice who was leading the court was sort of responsible for what happened

01:37:33.140 --> 01:37:36.940
[Guest]: during that time in terms of its jurisprudence and procedure.

01:37:36.940 --> 01:37:42.700
[Guest]: So we have no one to take ownership of the court because the churn is just so high.

01:37:42.700 --> 01:37:47.260
[Guest]: So I think one way of thinking about the incentive problem is like you said, you know, someone

01:37:47.260 --> 01:37:54.380
[Guest]: just like Justice Sikri on his last day of retirement just gives you the crazy nuclear

01:37:54.380 --> 01:37:58.900
[Guest]: judgment of Keshavanand Bharti and flies off into the sunset, right?

01:37:58.900 --> 01:38:03.400
[Guest]: The other possibility is someone says, I'm here for five years, my reputation depends

01:38:03.400 --> 01:38:09.820
[Guest]: on it, and I have a chance to really reform and put down some rules and actually enforce

01:38:09.820 --> 01:38:12.580
[Guest]: the rules and turn them into convention.

01:38:12.580 --> 01:38:14.860
[Guest]: So I think both are possible.

01:38:14.860 --> 01:38:18.380
[Guest]: The question is, what will happen and who will do it?

